Adults with no capacity for civil conduct or limited capacity for civil conduct shall have guardians appointed in the following order by persons with guardianship capacity:

(1) Spouse;

(2) Parents, children;

(3) Other close relatives;

(4) Other individuals or organizations willing to serve as guardians, with the consent of the residential committees, villagers committees, or civil affairs departments in the place of residence of the person under guardianship.

If the guardian meets one of the following conditions, the People's Court may, upon application by relevant individuals or organizations, revoke their guardian qualification, arrange necessary temporary guardianship measures, and appoint a guardian in accordance with the principle of best interests of the ward.

(1) Engaging in behaviors that seriously harm the physical and mental health of the ward;

(2) Failing to fulfill the obligations of guardianship, or unable to fulfill the obligations of guardianship and refusing to entrust part or all of the duties to others, resulting in the ward being in a dangerous situation;

(3) Engaging in other behaviors that seriously violate the legitimate rights and interests of the ward.

The individuals and organizations mentioned in this provision include: other persons who have legal guardianship qualifications, residential committees, village committees, schools, medical institutions, women's federations, disability associations, organizations for the protection of minors, legally established elderly organizations, and civil affairs departments.

If the individuals and organizations mentioned in the preceding paragraph, other than the civil affairs department, fail to apply to the People's Court for revocation of the guardian qualification in a timely manner, the civil affairs department shall apply to the People's Court.

One of the following circumstances shall result in the termination of guardianship:

(1) The ward acquires or regains full legal capacity;

(2) The guardian loses the capacity to be a guardian;

(3) The ward or the guardian dies;

(4) Other circumstances as determined by the People's Court to terminate the guardianship.

After the termination of guardianship, if the ward still requires guardianship, another guardian shall be determined in accordance with the law.

Section 3: Declaration of Disappearance and Declaration of Death

If any of the following reasons occur and the liquidation and cancellation registration are completed in accordance with the law, the legal entity will be terminated:

(1) The legal entity is dissolved;

(2) The legal entity is declared bankrupt;

(3) Other reasons as stipulated by laws.

If it is required by laws and administrative regulations for the termination of the legal entity to be approved by relevant authorities, it shall be carried out according to their provisions.

Non-incorporated organizations shall be dissolved for any of the following reasons:

(1) The term specified in the articles of association expires or other grounds for dissolution stipulated in the articles of association arise;

(2) The contributors or founders decide to dissolve the organization;

(3) Other circumstances stipulated by law.

Translation:

The dissolution of non-incorporated organizations can occur under any of the following circumstances:

(1) The term specified in the bylaws expires or other grounds for dissolution specified in the bylaws arise;

(2) The contributors or founders decide to dissolve the organization;

(3) Other circumstances stipulated by law.

Civil subjects enjoy intellectual property rights in accordance with the law.

Intellectual property rights refer to the exclusive rights that rights holders enjoy based on the following subjects:

- Works;
- Inventions, utility models, and industrial designs;
- Trademarks;
- Geographical indications;
- Trade secrets;
- Layout designs of integrated circuits;
- New varieties of plants;
- Other subjects as specified by laws.

One of the following circumstances shall result in the extinguishment of the right to rescission:

(1) If a party fails to exercise the right to rescission within one year from the date they become aware or should have become aware of the ground for rescission, or within three months from the date a party with a serious misunderstanding becomes aware or should have become aware of the ground for rescission;

(2) If a party subject to coercion fails to exercise the right to rescission within one year from the date the coercive act terminates;

(3) If a party, after becoming aware of the ground for rescission, expressly states or demonstrates through their conduct that they abandon the right to rescission.

If a party fails to exercise the right to rescission within five years from the date the civil legal act occurs, the right to rescission shall be extinguished.

If any of the following circumstances occur after the death of the principal, the agency acts implemented by the agent shall be valid:

(1) The agent does not know and is not expected to know about the principal's death;

(2) The successor of the principal acknowledges it;

(3) The authorization explicitly terminates the agency when the agency matters are completed;

(4) The agency has already been implemented before the principal's death and is continued for the benefit of the principal's successor.

The provisions of the preceding paragraph shall apply mutatis mutandis to the termination of legal persons or non-legal person organizations acting as principals.

Please translate the above content into English.

Termination of Legal Representation

One of the following circumstances shall result in the termination of legal representation:

(1) The principal regains or acquires full civil capacity;

(2) The agent loses civil capacity;

(3) The agent or the principal dies;

(4) Other circumstances as provided by law.

Chapter 8 Civil Liability.

There are various ways to assume civil liability:

1. Cease the infringement;
2. Remove obstacles;
3. Eliminate hazards;
4. Return the property;
5. Restore the original state;
6. Repair, remake, or replace;
7. Continue to perform;
8. Compensate for losses;
9. Pay liquidated damages;
10. Eliminate the impact and restore reputation; 
11. Make an apology;

If punitive damages are prescribed by law, they shall be imposed accordingly.

The above-mentioned ways of assuming civil liability may be applied separately or in combination.

During the last six months of the statute of limitations, if the exercise of the right to claim is hindered by any of the following obstacles, the statute of limitations shall be suspended:

(1) Force majeure;

(2) A person with no capacity for civil conduct or a person with restricted capacity for civil conduct has no legal representative, or the legal representative dies, loses capacity for civil conduct, or loses the power of attorney;

(3) The heir or estate administrator has not been determined after the commencement of inheritance;

(4) The right holder is controlled by the obligor or other person;

(5) Other obstacles that prevent the right holder from exercising the right to claim.

The statute of limitations shall resume after the elimination of the cause of suspension for a period of six months.

In any of the following circumstances, the statute of limitations for litigation is interrupted and the period of limitation for litigation is recalculated from the time of interruption or termination of the relevant proceedings:

(1) The obligee makes a performance request to the obligor;

(2) The obligor agrees to perform the obligation;

(3) The obligee files a lawsuit or applies for arbitration;

(4) Other circumstances that have the same effect as filing a lawsuit or applying for arbitration.

Translation: 

In any of the above circumstances, the statute of limitations for litigation is interrupted, and from the time of interruption or termination of the relevant proceedings, the period of limitation for litigation is recalculated.

The following requests are not subject to the provisions of the statute of limitations:

(1) Request to cease infringement, remove obstacles, or eliminate dangers;

(2) Right holders of real property rights and registered movable property rights requesting the return of property;

(3) Request for payment of maintenance fees or support fees;

(4) Other requests for which the statute of limitations does not apply under the law.

The articles of association of a limited liability company shall include the following provisions:

(1) Company name and registered address;

(2) Business scope of the company;

(3) Registered capital of the company;

(4) Names or names of shareholders;

(5) Shareholders' methods, amounts, and time of capital contribution;

(6) Company structure, including the method of formation, powers, and rules of procedure;

(7) Legal representative of the company;

(8) Any other matters deemed necessary by the shareholders' meeting to be specified in the articles of association.

Shareholders shall sign and affix their seals on the articles of association.

After the establishment of a limited liability company, it should issue capital certificates to its shareholders.

The capital certificate should contain the following information:

(1) Company name;

(2) Date of company establishment;

(3) Registered capital of the company;

(4) Shareholder's name or entity, amount of contribution, and date of contribution;

(5) Certificate number and issuance date.

The capital certificate should be stamped with the company's seal.

A limited liability company shall maintain a register of shareholders, recording the following information:

(1) The name or name and address of the shareholders;

(2) The amount of capital contributed by the shareholders;

(3) The certificate number of the contribution.

Shareholders recorded in the register of shareholders may exercise shareholder rights based on the register.

The company shall register the name or name and address of the shareholders with the company registration authority. In the event of changes to the registered information, the company shall carry out registration changes. Without registration or change registration, the company may not oppose third parties.

Shareholders shall exercise the following powers:

(1) Determine the company's business policies and investment plans;

(2) Elect and replace directors and supervisors who are not appointed by employee representatives and determine matters related to their remuneration;

(3) Review and approve the reports of the board of directors;

(4) Review and approve the reports of the board of supervisors or supervisors;

(5) Review and approve the company's annual financial budget plan and final accounts plan;

(6) Review and approve the company's profit distribution plan and loss offset plan;

(7) Make resolutions on increasing or reducing the registered capital of the company;

(8) Make resolutions on the issuance of corporate bonds;

(9) Make resolutions on the company's merger, division, dissolution, liquidation, or change of corporate form;

(10) Amend the company's articles of association;

(11) Other powers specified in the company's articles of association.

If the shareholders unanimously agree in writing on the matters listed in the preceding paragraph, there is no need to convene a shareholders' meeting. The decision can be made directly, and all shareholders shall sign and seal the decision document.

The Board of Directors is responsible to the Shareholders' Meeting and exercises the following powers:

1. Convening the Shareholders' Meeting and reporting on its work;
2. Implementing the resolutions of the Shareholders' Meeting;
3. Deciding on the company's business plans and investment proposals;
4. Formulating the annual financial budget and final accounts of the company;
5. Formulating the profit distribution plan and loss compensation plan of the company;
6. Formulating proposals for increasing or reducing the registered capital of the company and issuing corporate bonds;
7. Formulating proposals for the merger, division, dissolution, or change of the company's legal form;
8. Deciding on the establishment of internal management institutions of the company;
9. Deciding on the appointment or dismissal of the company's General Manager and their remuneration, and based on the General Manager's nomination, deciding on the appointment or dismissal of the Deputy General Manager, Chief Financial Officer, and their remuneration;
10. Establishing the basic management systems of the company;
11. Exercising other powers as stipulated in the company's articles of association.

A limited liability company may establish a manager who is appointed or dismissed by the board of directors. The manager is responsible to the board and exercises the following powers:

- Oversee the company's production and management operations and implement board resolutions;
- Organize and implement the company's annual business plan and investment proposals;
- Draft a plan for the internal management structure of the company;
- Formulate the company's basic management systems;
- Establish specific regulations for the company;
- Propose the appointment or dismissal of deputy managers and financial officers;
- Decide on the appointment or dismissal of other management personnel, excluding those that should be decided by the board of directors;
- Exercise other powers as granted by the board of directors.

If the company's articles of association provide otherwise, the manager's powers are subject to their provisions.

The manager shall attend board meetings.

The supervisor of a company with a supervisory board and a company without a supervisory board shall exercise the following powers:

(1) Inspect the company's finances;

(2) Supervise the actions of directors and senior executives in performing their duties, propose dismissal of directors and senior executives who violate laws, administrative regulations, company articles or resolutions of the shareholders' general meeting;

(3) Demand correction from directors and senior executives whose actions have harmed the company's interests;

(4) Propose the convening of an extraordinary shareholders' general meeting, and convene and preside over the shareholders' general meeting when the board of directors fails to perform its obligations to convene and preside over the shareholders' general meeting as provided in this Law;

(5) Propose motions at shareholders' general meetings;

(6) File a lawsuit against directors and senior executives in accordance with the provisions of Article 151 of this Law;

(7) Other powers specified in the company's articles of association.

In the event of any of the following circumstances, a shareholder who voted against the resolution at the shareholders' meeting may request the company to repurchase its equity at a reasonable price:

(1) The company fails to distribute profits to shareholders for five consecutive years, while the company has made continuous profits and meets the conditions for profit distribution as provided in this Law;

(2) The company merges, divides, or transfers its major assets;

(3) The company's articles of association provide for the expiration of the business term or other grounds for dissolution specified in the articles, and the shareholders' meeting passes a resolution to amend the articles to allow the company to continue its existence.

If the shareholder and the company fail to reach an agreement on the repurchase of equity within sixty days from the date of the adoption of the resolution at the shareholders' meeting, the shareholder may file a lawsuit with the People's Court within ninety days from the date of the adoption of the resolution at the shareholders' meeting.

The articles of association of a limited liability company shall include the following matters:

(1) The company name and registered address;

(2) The business scope of the company;

(3) The method of establishment of the company;

(4) The total number of shares, the par value per share, and the registered capital of the company;

(5) The names or names of the promoters, the number of shares subscribed by them, the method of contribution, and the time of contribution;

(6) The composition, powers, and rules of procedure of the board of directors;

(7) The legal representative of the company;

(8) The composition, powers, and rules of procedure of the supervisory board;

(9) The method of profit distribution of the company;

(10) The causes of dissolution of the company and the liquidation method;

(11) The method of notice and announcement of the company;

(12) Other matters that the shareholders' meeting considers necessary to stipulate.

The prospectus should include the company's articles of association formulated by the initiators, and clearly state the following matters:

(1) The number of shares subscribed by the initiators;

(2) The face value and issue price per share;

(3) The total number of bearer shares issued;

(4) The purpose of raising funds;

(5) The rights and obligations of the subscribers;

(6) The start and end dates of this fundraising, as well as the explanation that subscribers can withdraw their subscribed shares if the fundraising is not fully completed within the specified period.

The board of directors should submit the following documents to the company registration authority within thirty days after the establishment conference, in order to apply for registration:

(1) Company registration application form;

(2) Minutes of the establishment conference;

(3) Articles of Association;

(4) Capital verification certificate;

(5) Appointment documents and identification proof of the legal representative, directors, and supervisors;

(6) Proof of the legal person qualification or identification proof of the promoters;

(7) Proof of company domicile.

If a public offering of shares is used to establish a joint stock limited company, the approval document of the State Council's securities regulatory authority should also be submitted to the company registration authority.

The initiators of a limited liability company shall bear the following responsibilities:

(1) Joint liability for the debts and expenses arising from the establishment acts when the company cannot be established;

(2) Joint liability for the refund of the subscribed capital and the calculation of interest on bank deposits for the period when the company cannot be established;

(3) If the initiators cause damage to the interests of the company due to their negligence during the establishment process, they shall be liable for compensation to the company.

The shareholders' meeting should be held annually. In any of the following circumstances, an interim shareholders' meeting should be convened within two months:

(1) When the number of directors falls below the minimum required by this Law or the number specified in the company's articles of association, two-thirds of the required number;

(2) When the accumulated losses of the company reach one-third of the total paid-in capital that remains unrecovered;

(3) When a shareholder or a group of shareholders who individually or collectively hold more than ten percent of the company's shares makes a request;

(4) When deemed necessary by the board of directors;

(5) When proposed by the supervisory board;

(6) Other circumstances specified in the company's articles of association.

Stocks are issued in written form or in any other form specified by the State Council Securities Supervision and Administration Institution.

Stock certificates should include the following main items:

(1) Company name;

(2) Date of company establishment;

(3) Type of stock, face value, and the number of shares represented;

(4) Stock number.

Stock certificates are signed by the legal representative and stamped by the company.

For stocks held by promoters, the label "Promoter Shares" should be indicated.

If a company issues registered shares, it shall keep a shareholder register recording the following items:

(1) The name or company name and address of the shareholder;
(2) The number of shares held by each shareholder;
(3) The serial number of the shares held by each shareholder;
(4) The date on which each shareholder acquires the shares.

If a company issues bearer shares, it shall record the quantity, serial number, and date of issuance of the shares.

The shareholders' meeting shall make resolutions on the following matters regarding the issuance of new shares:

(1) Types and amounts of new shares;

(2) Issuance price of new shares;

(3) Commencement and end dates of new share issuance;

(4) Types and amounts of new shares to be issued to existing shareholders.

The company is prohibited from acquiring its own shares, except in the following circumstances:

1. To reduce the company's registered capital;
2. To merge with another company holding shares of the company;
3. To award shares to the employees of the company;
4. If a shareholder opposes a resolution of the shareholders' meeting regarding company merger or division and requests the company to acquire his/her shares.

The acquisition of the company's shares due to the reasons stated in the first to third items above shall be subject to the resolution of the shareholders' meeting. If the acquired shares fall within the scope of the first item, the company shall cancel them within ten days from the date of acquisition; if they fall within the scope of the second or fourth item, the company shall transfer or cancel them within six months.

The acquisition of the company's shares, as stipulated in the third item of the first clause, shall not exceed five percent of the total issued shares of the company; the funds used for the acquisition shall be paid from the company's after-tax profits; the acquired shares shall be transferred to employees within one year.

The company shall not accept its own shares as the subject of pledge.

Anyone who falls under any of the following circumstances shall not serve as a director, supervisor, or senior executive of the company:

(1) Incapable of civil conduct or has limited civil conduct capacity;

(2) Sentenced to imprisonment for embezzlement, bribery, misappropriation of funds, or undermining the socialist market economy order, with a term not exceeding five years, or deprived of political rights due to a crime, with a term not exceeding five years;

(3) Served as a director, factory director, or manager of a bankrupt company or enterprise, and personally liable for the bankruptcy, within three years from the completion of the bankruptcy liquidation of the company or enterprise;

(4) Served as the legal representative of a company or enterprise whose business license was revoked or ordered to close due to violations, and personally liable, within three years from the date of revocation of the business license;

(5) Personal debts of significant amounts have not been fully repaid upon maturity. 

If the company violates the provisions mentioned above and elects, appoints, or hires directors, supervisors, or senior executives, such election, appointment, or hiring shall be deemed invalid.

If a director, supervisor, or senior executive encounters any of the circumstances listed in the first paragraph during the tenure, the company shall terminate their position.

Directors and senior management personnel shall not engage in the following behaviors:

(1) Misappropriating company funds;

(2) Opening personal accounts or accounts in other individuals' names to store company funds;

(3) Violating the provisions of the company's articles of association and lending company funds to others or providing guarantees with company property without the consent of the shareholders' meeting, general meeting of shareholders, or board of directors;

(4) Entering into contracts or conducting transactions with the company without the consent of the shareholders' meeting, general meeting of shareholders, or in violation of the provisions of the company's articles of association;

(5) Using their position to seek business opportunities belonging to the company for themselves or others, either through self-operation or operating similar businesses for others, without the consent of the shareholders' meeting or general meeting of shareholders;

(6) Receiving commissions from transactions between others and the company for their own benefit;

(7) Disclosing company secrets without authorization;

(8) Engaging in other behaviors that violate their fiduciary duty to the company.

The income obtained by directors and senior management personnel in violation of the above provisions shall be owned by the company.

After the application for the issuance of corporate bonds has been approved by the department authorized by the State Council, the method of raising funds through corporate bonds should be announced.

The main contents to be included in the method of raising corporate bonds are as follows:

(1) Company name;

(2) Purpose of raising funds through bonds;

(3) Total amount of bonds and face value of bonds;

(4) Determination method of bond interest rate;

(5) Term and method of principal and interest payment;

(6) Bond collateral situation;

(7) Issuance price and issuance period of bonds;

(8) Net assets of the company;

(9) Total amount of corporate bonds issued but not yet due;

(10) Underwriting institutions for corporate bonds.

The company should keep a bond stub book when issuing corporate bonds.

For registered corporate bonds, the following information should be recorded in the bond stub book:

(1) Name or title and address of the bond holder;
(2) Date when the bond holder acquired the bond and the bond number;
(3) Total amount of the bond, face value, interest rate, and maturity and payment method;
(4) Issuance date of the bond.

For bearer corporate bonds, the bond stub book should record the total amount, interest rate, repayment term and method, issuance date, and bond number.

The company may be dissolved for the following reasons:

(1) The business term stipulated in the company articles expires or other dissolution causes specified in the company articles occur;

(2) Resolution of dissolution passed by the shareholders' meeting or the general meeting of shareholders;

(3) Dissolution is necessary due to company merger or division;

(4) The business license is revoked, ordered to shut down, or revoked in accordance with the law;

(5) Dissolution ordered by a people's court in accordance with Article 182 of this law.

During the liquidation period, the liquidation team exercises the following powers:
(1) Clearing company assets and preparing a balance sheet and inventory of assets;
(2) Notifying and announcing creditors;
(3) Dealing with unresolved business related to the liquidation;
(4) Paying off outstanding taxes and taxes generated during the liquidation process;
(5) Sorting out claims and debts;
(6) Handling the remaining assets after the company's debts have been settled;
(7) Representing the company in civil litigation activities.

The following labor disputes between employers and employees within the territory of the People's Republic of China shall be governed by this Law:

(1) Disputes arising from the confirmation of employment relationship;

(2) Disputes arising from the conclusion, performance, amendment, rescission, and termination of labor contracts;

(3) Disputes arising from dismissal, termination, resignation, or quitting of employment;

(4) Disputes arising from work hours, rest and leave, social insurance, benefits, training, and labor protection;

(5) Disputes arising from labor remuneration, work-related injury medical expenses, economic compensation, or indemnity;

(6) Other labor disputes as prescribed by laws and regulations.

In case of a labor dispute, the parties involved can apply for mediation to the following mediation organizations:

(1) Enterprise Labor Dispute Mediation Committee;

(2) Grassroots people's mediation organizations established in accordance with the law;

(3) Organizations with the function of labor dispute mediation established in towns and streets.

The Enterprise Labor Dispute Mediation Committee is composed of representatives of employees and representatives of the enterprise. The representatives of employees are selected from members of the trade union or elected by all employees, while the representatives of the enterprise are designated by the enterprise's management. The director of the Enterprise Labor Dispute Mediation Committee is appointed from among the members of the trade union or individuals nominated by both parties.

The Labor Dispute Arbitration Committee is composed of representatives from the labor administration department, union representatives, and representatives from the enterprise side. The members of the Labor Dispute Arbitration Committee should be odd in number.

The Labor Dispute Arbitration Committee performs the following responsibilities in accordance with the law:

(1) Appointing and dismissing full-time or part-time arbitrators;

(2) Accepting labor dispute cases;

(3) Discussing major or complicated labor dispute cases;

(4) Supervising arbitration activities.

The Labor Dispute Arbitration Committee establishes administrative offices to handle the daily work of the Labor Dispute Arbitration Committee.

The Labor Dispute Arbitration Commission shall establish a roster of arbitrators.

Arbitrators shall be fair and upright, and meet one of the following conditions:

(1) Former judges;

(2) Engaged in legal research or teaching and hold a senior professional title;

(3) Have a minimum of five years of experience in the field of labor resource management or labor union work, with knowledge of the law;

(4) Have practiced as a lawyer for at least three years.

The arbitrator should recuse themselves if they fall under any of the following circumstances, and the parties also have the right to orally or in writing submit a recusal request:

(1) They are relatives of any of the parties involved in the case or their representatives;

(2) They have a vested interest in the outcome of the case;

(3) They have other relationships with the parties or their representatives that may affect impartial decision-making;

(4) They have secretly met with the parties or their representatives or have accepted their invitations or gifts.

The Arbitration Committee for Labor Disputes should promptly make a decision on the recusal request and notify the parties orally or in writing.

For the following labor disputes, unless otherwise stipulated in this law, the arbitration award shall be final and binding, and the award shall take effect from the date of its issuance:

(1) Disputes over the payment of labor remuneration, work-related medical expenses, economic compensation, or damages, which do not exceed twelve times the local monthly minimum wage standard;

(2) Disputes arising from the implementation of the state's labor standards regarding working hours, rest and leave, social insurance, and other aspects.

The employer can apply for the revocation of the arbitration award to the Intermediate People's Court in the place where the labor dispute arbitration commission is located within 30 days from the date of receiving the arbitration award, if there is evidence that proves one of the following circumstances provided in Article 47 of this law:

(1) There is a clear error in the application of laws and regulations;

(2) The labor dispute arbitration commission lacks jurisdiction;

(3) Violation of statutory procedures;

(4) The evidence on which the award is based is fabricated;

(5) The opposing party has concealed evidence that is sufficient to influence a fair determination;

(6) The arbitrator involved in the arbitration has engaged in bribery, corruption, or acts of rendering an unjust arbitrational decision.

The people's court, after examining and verifying the award through a collegial panel, shall make a ruling to revoke if any of the above circumstances stipulated in the preceding paragraph are found to exist.

If the arbitration award is revoked by the people's court, the party can file a lawsuit with the people's court within15 days from the date of receiving the ruling regarding the labor dispute issue.

An insurance contract shall include the following matters:

(1) Name and address of the insurer;

(2) Name or title and address of the policyholder, the insured, as well as the beneficiary's name or title and address in case of personal insurance;

(3) The subject matter of insurance;

(4) Insurance liability and exclusions;

(5) Insurance period and commencement of insurance liability;

(6) Insurance amount;

(7) Insurance premium and payment method;

(8) Method of compensation or payment of insurance benefits;

(9) Liability for breach of contract and dispute resolution;

(10) Date of contract conclusion.

The policyholder and insurer may agree on other matters related to the insurance.

The beneficiary refers to the person designated by the insured or policyholder in the life insurance contract, who enjoys the right to claim insurance benefits. The policyholder or insured may be the beneficiary.

The insurance amount refers to the maximum limit of the insurer's liability for compensation or payment of insurance benefits.

The following clauses in the insurance contract entered into using the format terms provided by the insurer shall be deemed invalid:

(1) Exempting the insurer from legal obligations or increasing the responsibilities of the policyholder or the insured;

(2) Excluding the rights enjoyed by the policyholder, the insured, or the beneficiary as stipulated by law.

The insured has insurance interests in the following individuals:

(1) Himself/herself;
(2) Spouse, children, parents;
(3) Other family members or close relatives who have a support or care relationship with the insured, excluding those mentioned in the preceding items;
(4) Workers who have a labor relationship with the insured.

In addition to the above provisions, if the insured agrees to have the policyholder enter into a contract on their behalf, it is deemed that the policyholder has insurance interests in the insured.

If the policyholder does not have insurance interests in the insured when entering into the contract, the contract is invalid.

In the event that the insured passes away, the insurance proceeds shall be treated as the estate of the insured, and the insurer shall fulfill the obligation to pay the insurance proceeds in accordance with the provisions of the Inheritance Law of the People's Republic of China under the following circumstances:

1. If no beneficiary is designated or the designated beneficiary is unclear and cannot be determined;

2. If the beneficiary predeceases the insured and there are no other beneficiaries;

3. If the beneficiary loses the right to receive the benefits or voluntarily renounces the right to receive the benefits, and there are no other beneficiaries.

If both the beneficiary and the insured pass away in the same incident and the order of death cannot be determined, it shall be presumed that the beneficiary predeceased the insured.

In the case of one of the following circumstances, unless otherwise agreed in the contract, the insurer shall reduce the insurance premium and refund the corresponding premium on a daily basis:

(1) The relevant circumstances on which the insurance premium rate is determined have changed and the degree of risk of the insured subject has significantly decreased;

(2) The insurance value of the insured subject has significantly decreased.

When an insurance company applies to establish a branch institution, it shall submit a written application to the insurance supervision and management authority and provide the following materials:

(1) Application for establishment;

(2) Three-year business development plan and market analysis materials for the proposed institution;

(3) Resumes and relevant supporting documents of the proposed senior management personnel;

(4) Other materials required by the insurance supervision and management authority of the State Council.

Insurance companies shall obtain approval from the insurance supervision and administration authority in the following circumstances:

(1) Change of name;
(2) Change of registered capital;
(3) Change of business premises of the company or branch;
(4) Revocation of branch;
(5) Company division or merger;
(6) Modification of the company's articles of association;
(7) Change of shareholders holding more than 5% of the capital of a limited liability company or shareholders holding more than 5% of the shares of a limited liability company;
(8) Other circumstances stipulated by the insurance supervision and administration authority of the State Council.

After prioritizing bankruptcy expenses and common debts, the bankruptcy assets shall be cleared in the following order:

(1) Outstanding salaries, medical and disability allowances, pension and medical insurance fees that should be transferred to employees' personal accounts, as well as compensation that should be paid to employees as regulated by law and administrative regulations;

(2) Compensation or payment of insurance benefits;

(3) Social insurance fees and outstanding taxes owed by insurance companies, excluding those mentioned in item (1);

(4) Regular bankruptcy claims.

If the bankruptcy assets are insufficient to fulfill the clearing requirements in the same order, they shall be distributed proportionally.

The salaries of directors and supervisors, as well as senior management personnel of bankrupt insurance companies, shall be calculated based on the average salary of the company's employees.

Insurance company's business scope: 

(1) Personal insurance business, including life insurance, health insurance, accident insurance, and other insurance businesses; 

(2) Property insurance business, including property loss insurance, liability insurance, credit insurance, guarantee insurance, and other insurance businesses; 

(3) Other insurance-related businesses approved by the insurance regulatory authority of the State Council. 

Insurance companies are not allowed to engage in both personal insurance business and property insurance business. However, insurance companies that operate property insurance business may, with the approval of the insurance regulatory authority of the State Council, engage in short-term health insurance business and accident insurance business.

Insurance companies shall engage in insurance operations within the business scope approved by the insurance regulatory authority of the State Council.

With the approval of the State Council's insurance supervision and management authority, insurance companies can engage in the following reinsurance businesses as stipulated in Article 95 of this Law:

(1) Ceding insurance;

(2) Accepting insurance.

Insurance companies shall contribute to the insurance guarantee fund.

The insurance guarantee fund shall be centrally managed and used in the following situations:

(1) Providing relief to policyholders, insured persons, or beneficiaries when an insurance company is revoked or declared bankrupt;

(2) Providing relief to insurance companies that have legally accepted their life insurance contracts when an insurance company is revoked or declared bankrupt;

(3) Other situations specified by the State Council.

The specific measures for the collection, management, and use of the insurance guarantee fund shall be formulated by the State Council.

Insurance companies and their employees shall not engage in the following behaviors in insurance business activities:

(1) Deceiving the policyholder, the insured, or the beneficiary;

(2) Concealing important information related to the insurance contract from the policyholder;

(3) Obstructing the policyholder from fulfilling the obligation of truthful disclosure as prescribed by this law, or inducing them not to fulfill the obligation of truthful disclosure as prescribed by this law;

(4) Providing or promising to provide the policyholder, the insured, or the beneficiary with insurance premium rebates or other benefits outside the provisions of the insurance contract;

(5) Refusing to perform the obligations of compensation or payment of insurance benefits as stipulated in the insurance contract in accordance with the law;

(6) Intentionally fabricating non-occurred insurance accidents, falsifying insurance contracts, or intentionally exaggerating the degree of loss of occurred insurance accidents to fraudulently claim insurance benefits or seek other improper gains;

(7) Embezzling, intercepting, or misappropriating insurance premiums;

(8) Entrusting institutions without legal qualifications to engage in insurance sales activities;

(9) Using the conduct of insurance business to seek improper gains for other institutions or individuals;

(10) Engaging in illegal activities such as fabricating insurance intermediary business or fabricating withdrawals to collect fees using insurance agents, insurance brokers, or insurance assessment institutions;

(11) Damaging the commercial reputation of competitors by fabricating or spreading false facts, or disturbing the order of the insurance market through other unfair competition behaviors;

(12) Disclosing business secrets of the policyholder or the insured that are known in business activities.

If an insurance company violates the provisions of this Law and engages in any of the following acts, the insurance supervision and management authority shall order it to make corrections and impose a fine of not less than 50,000 yuan and not more than 300,000 yuan:

(1) Excessive coverage, with serious circumstances;

(2) Insuring individuals without capacity for civil conduct with death as a condition for payment of insurance benefits.

If any of the following actions violates this Law, the insurance regulatory authority shall order them to make corrections and impose a fine of no less than 50,000 yuan and no more than 300,000 yuan; if the circumstances are serious, their business scope may be restricted, or they may be ordered to stop accepting new business or revoke their business license:

(1) Failing to deposit the margin as required or improperly using the margin;

(2) Failing to withdraw or carry forward any reserve for liability as required;

(3) Failing to pay the insurance guarantee fund or withdraw the public funds as required;

(4) Failing to handle reinsurance as required;

(5) Failing to use insurance company funds as required;

(6) Establishing branch organizations without approval;

(7) Failing to apply for approval of insurance clauses or insurance premium rates as required.

Insurance agencies or insurance brokers that violate the provisions of this Law and engage in any of the following acts shall be ordered to correct them by the insurance supervision and administration authority and be fined an amount between 20,000 and 100,000 yuan; if the circumstances are serious, they shall be ordered to suspend business for rectification or have their business license revoked:

(1) Failing to deposit guarantees according to the regulations or failing to purchase professional liability insurance;

(2) Failing to establish a special account to record the income and expenses of the business according to the regulations.

If any of the following acts violates the provisions of this law, the insurance supervision and administration authority shall order the rectification within a time limit; if the rectification is not made within the time limit, a fine of not less than ten thousand yuan but not more than one hundred thousand yuan shall be imposed:

(1) Failure to submit or keep reports, statements, documents, or materials as required, or failure to provide relevant information or materials as required;

(2) Failure to submit insurance clauses and insurance premium rates for filing as required;

(3) Failure to disclose information as required.

If any of the following acts violates the provisions of this Law, the insurance regulatory authority shall order correction and impose a fine of no less than one hundred thousand yuan and no more than five hundred thousand yuan; if the circumstances are serious, it may restrict its business scope, order it to stop accepting new business or revoke its business license:

(1) preparing or providing false reports, statements, documents or materials;

(2) refusing or obstructing supervision and inspection in accordance with the law;

(3) failing to use approved or recorded insurance clauses and insurance rates as stipulated.

Personnel engaged in supervision and management work by insurance regulatory authorities shall be subject to disciplinary action in accordance with the law if they fall into one of the following situations:

(1) Violating regulations on approving the establishment of institutions;

(2) Violating regulations on the approval of insurance clauses and premium rates;

(3) Violating regulations on conducting on-site inspections;

(4) Violating regulations on accessing accounts or freezing funds;

(5) Disclosing commercial secrets of units and individuals known to them;

(6) Violating regulations on the imposition of administrative penalties;

(7) Engaging in other acts of abuse of power or neglect of duty.

The registration institution shall fulfill the following responsibilities:
(1) Verify the ownership certificate and other necessary documents provided by the applicant;
(2) Inquire the applicant about relevant registration matters;
(3) Register relevant matters truthfully and promptly;
(4) Other responsibilities prescribed by laws and administrative regulations.
If further proof is needed for the relevant circumstances of the applied real property, the registration institution may require the applicant to submit additional materials and may conduct on-site inspections if necessary.

Registration agencies shall not engage in the following activities:
(1) Requiring property evaluation for real estate;
(2) Conducting repetitive registration in the name of annual inspection or similar activities;
(3) Engaging in other activities beyond the scope of registration responsibilities.

Collective-owned real estate and movable property include:
(1) Land, forests, mountains, grasslands, wastelands, and tidal flats that are legally designated as collective-owned property;
(2) Buildings, production facilities, and agricultural water conservancy facilities that are collectively owned;
(3) Educational, scientific, cultural, health, and sports facilities that are collectively owned;
(4) Other immovable and movable property that is collectively owned.

The immovable and movable properties collectively owned by the peasant collective belong to the collective ownership of the members of the collective.
The following matters shall be decided by the members of the collective through the statutory procedure:
(1) Land contracting schemes and the leasing of land to units or individuals outside the collective;
(2) Adjustments to the contracting of individual land-use rights among the land contract operators;
(3) The utilization and distribution methods of land compensation fees and other expenses;
(4) Changes in ownership of enterprises funded by the collective;
(5) Other matters stipulated by law.

The following matters shall be decided jointly by the property owners:

(1) Formulating and amending the agenda rules of the owners' meetings;

(2) Formulating and amending the management regulations of the buildings and their ancillary facilities;

(3) Electing or replacing members of the owners' committee;

(4) Appointing or dismissing property service enterprises or other managers;

(5) Raising and using funds for the maintenance of the buildings and their ancillary facilities;

(6) Renovating or reconstructing the buildings and their ancillary facilities;

(7) Other major matters related to co-ownership and joint management rights.

Decisions on the matters specified in the fifth and sixth items above shall require the consent of more than two-thirds of the owners who occupy more than two-thirds of the total area of the property and more than two-thirds of the total number of owners. Decisions on other matters specified above shall require the consent of owners who own more than half of the total area of the property and more than half of the total number of owners.

If a person transfers real estate or chattels to the transferee without authority, the owner has the right to recover the property. However, the transferee will acquire ownership of the real estate or chattels under the following circumstances, unless otherwise provided by law:
(1) The transferee acquired the real estate or chattels in good faith;
(2) The transfer was made at a reasonable price;
(3) The transferred real estate or chattels have been registered as required by law, or if registration is not required, they have been delivered to the transferee.
If the transferee acquires ownership of the real estate or chattels in accordance with the provisions above, the original owner has the right to claim compensation for any loss from the person without disposal rights.
The provisions of the aforementioned two paragraphs shall apply mutatis mutandis to the good-faith acquisition of other property rights by the parties.

If the establishment of the right to use construction land is conducted through bidding, auction, agreement, etc., the parties concerned shall enter into a written contract for the transfer of the right to use the construction land.

The contract for the transfer of the right to use construction land generally includes the following provisions:

(1) Name and address of the parties concerned;

(2) Land boundaries, area, etc.;

(3) Space occupied by buildings, structures, and their ancillary facilities;

(4) Land use;

(5) Duration of use;

(6) Transfer fee and its payment method;

(7) Dispute resolution method.

To establish a servitude, the parties involved must enter into a written servitude contract.

The servitude contract generally includes the following clauses:
(1) The names or names, addresses of the parties involved;
(2) The location of the servient land and dominant land;
(3) The purpose and methods of use;
(4) The duration of the servitude;
(5) The fees and payment methods;
(6) Dispute resolution methods.

The extinguishment of security rights shall occur in one of the following circumstances:
(1) The principal claim is extinguished;
(2) The security rights are realized;
(3) The creditor renounces the security rights;
(4) Other circumstances specified by law for the extinguishment of security rights.

Debtors or third parties have the right to mortgage the following properties that can be disposed of:
1. Buildings and other structures attached to land;
2. Right to use construction land;
3. Land contracting and operating rights obtained through bidding, auction, public negotiation, etc.;
4. Production equipment, raw materials, semi-finished products, and finished products;
5. Buildings, ships, and aircraft under construction;
6. Vehicles for transportation;
7. Other properties not prohibited from mortgage by laws and administrative regulations.
The mortgagor may mortgage the aforementioned properties together.

The following properties may not be mortgaged:
(1) Land ownership;
(2) Collective land use rights such as arable land, homesteads, self-retained land, and self-retained mountains, except those allowed to be mortgaged by law;
(3) Educational facilities, medical and health facilities, and other social welfare facilities of public welfare-oriented institutions and social organizations such as schools, kindergartens, and hospitals;
(4) Properties with unclear or disputed ownership or use rights;
(5) Properties that have been sealed, seized, or placed under supervision according to law;
(6) Other properties that are prohibited from being mortgaged by laws and administrative regulations.

The establishment of a mortgage requires the parties to enter into a mortgage agreement in writing.
The mortgage agreement generally includes the following clauses:
(1) The type and amount of the secured debt;
(2) The deadline for the debtor to fulfill the debt;
(3) The name, quantity, quality, condition, location, ownership or right of use of the mortgaged property;
(4) The scope of the guarantee.

According to Article 181 of this law, the determination of the mortgaged property shall be made when one of the following circumstances occurs:
(1) The maturity of the debt has arrived, but the creditor's rights have not been realized;
(2) The mortgagor is declared bankrupt or revoked;
(3) The parties have agreed on the realization of the mortgage;
(4) Other circumstances that seriously affect the realization of the creditor's rights.

Translation: 
If the mortgage is established according to Article 181 of this law, the mortgaged property shall be determined in one of the following situations:
(1) The debt is due, but the creditor's rights have not been realized;
(2) The mortgagor is declared bankrupt or revoked;
(3) The parties have agreed to realize the mortgage rights;
(4) Other circumstances that seriously affect the realization of the creditor's rights.

The creditor's claim under the mortgage shall be determined under one of the following circumstances:
(1) The predetermined period for the determination of the claim has expired;
(2) If there is no predetermined period for the determination of the claim or the agreement is unclear, the creditor or the mortgagor may request the determination of the claim after a period of two years from the date of the establishment of the maximum amount of the mortgage;
(3) The occurrence of a new claim is impossible;
(4) The mortgaged property is sealed or seized;
(5) The debtor or the mortgagor is declared bankrupt or revoked;
(6) Other circumstances specified by law for the determination of the claim.

Note: The translation provided above is a general translation and may not accurately reflect the legal terminology in English. It is recommended to consult a professional legal translator for accurate translation in a legal context.

In order to establish a pledge, the parties involved should enter into a pledge contract in written form.
A pledge contract generally includes the following clauses:
(1) The type and amount of the guaranteed debt;
(2) The deadline for the debtor to fulfill the obligation;
(3) The name, quantity, quality, and condition of the pledged property;
(4) The scope of the guarantee;
(5) The time of delivery of the pledged property.

The following rights, which can be disposed of by the debtor or a third party, can be pledged:

(1) Bills of exchange, checks, promissory notes;
(2) Bonds, certificates of deposit;
(3) Warehouse receipts, bills of lading;
(4) Transferable fund shares, equity interests;
(5) Property rights in transferable registered trademarks, patent rights, copyright and other intellectual property rights;
(6) Accounts receivable;
(7) Other property rights that can be pledged as stipulated by laws and administrative regulations.

To apply for motor vehicle registration, the following proofs and documents shall be submitted:

(1) Identification proof of the vehicle owner;
(2) Proof of the origin of the motor vehicle;
(3) Certificate of compliance with factory standards or import certificate for imported motor vehicles;
(4) Proof of payment of vehicle purchase tax or exemption certificate;
(5) Other proofs and documents required by laws and regulations for motor vehicle registration.

The traffic management department of the public security organs shall complete the examination of motor vehicle registration within five working days from the date of acceptance of the application. If the conditions provided in the preceding paragraph are met, the motor vehicle registration certificate, license plate, and driving license shall be issued. If the conditions are not met, the reasons for refusal shall be explained to the applicant.

No unit or individual other than the traffic management department of the public security organs shall issue motor vehicle license plates or request the motor vehicle to display other license plates, except as otherwise provided in this Law.

The style of motor vehicle registration certificate, license plate, and driving license shall be prescribed and supervised by the public security department of the State Council.

zh_law_content:
申请机动车登记,应当提交以下证明、凭证:

(一)机动车所有人的身份证明;

(二)机动车来历证明;

(三)机动车整车出厂合格证明或者进口机动车进口凭证;

(四)车辆购置税的完税证明或者免税凭证;

(五)法律、行政法规规定应当在机动车登记时提交的其他证明、凭证。

公安机关交通管理部门应当自受理申请之日起五个工作日内完成机动车登记审查工作,对符合前款规定条件的,应当发放机动车登记证书、号牌和行驶证;对不符合前款规定条件的,应当向申请人说明不予登记的理由。

公安机关交通管理部门以外的任何单位或者个人不得发放机动车号牌或者要求机动车悬挂其他号牌,本法另有规定的除外。

机动车登记证书、号牌、行驶证的式样由国务院公安部门规定并监制。

law_content:
One of the following circumstances shall be registered accordingly:

(1) Transfer of ownership of a motor vehicle;

(2) Change in the registered information of a motor vehicle;

(3) Use of a motor vehicle as collateral;

(4) Decommissioning of a motor vehicle.

zh_law_content:
有下列情形之一的,应当办理相应的登记:

(一)机动车所有权发生转移的;

(二)机动车登记内容变更的;

(三)机动车用作抵押的;

(四)机动车报废的。

任何单位或者个人不得有下列行为:

(一)拼装机动车或者擅自改变机动车已登记的结构、构造或者特征;

(二)改变机动车型号、发动机号、车架号或者车辆识别代号;

(三)伪造、变造或者使用伪造、变造的机动车登记证书、号牌、行驶证、检验合格标志、保险标志;

(四)使用其他机动车的登记证书、号牌、行驶证、检验合格标志、保险标志。

law_content:
When driving in the same lane, the following conditions prohibit overtaking:
(1) The vehicle in front is making a left turn, U-turn, or overtaking another vehicle;
(2) There is a possibility of oncoming traffic;
(3) The vehicle in front is an emergency vehicle such as a police car, fire truck, ambulance, or engineering rescue vehicle;
(4) Passing is not allowed on roads such as railway crossings, intersections, narrow bridges, bends, steep slopes, tunnels, pedestrian crossings, and busy urban areas. 

In all cases, the following vehicle must maintain a safe distance that allows for emergency braking measures.

zh_law_content:
同车道行驶的机动车,后车应当与前车保持足以采取紧急制动措施的安全距离。有下列情形之一的,不得超车:

(一)前车正在左转弯、掉头、超车的;

(二)与对面来车有会车可能的;

(三)前车为执行紧急任务的警车、消防车、救护车、工程救险车的;

(四)行经铁路道口、交叉路口、窄桥、弯道、陡坡、隧道、人行横道、市区交通流量大的路段等没有超车条件的。

law_content:
Traffic police shall avoid handling the following cases regarding road traffic safety violations and traffic accidents:

(1) If they are the parties involved or close relatives of the parties involved in the case;

(2) If they or their close relatives have a vested interest in the case;

(3) If they have any other relationship with the parties involved in the case that may affect the impartial handling of the case.

zh_law_content:
交通警察调查处理道路交通安全违法行为和交通事故,有下列情形之一的,应当回避:

(一)是本案的当事人或者当事人的近亲属;

(二)本人或者其近亲属与本案有利害关系;

(三)与本案当事人有其他关系,可能影响案件的公正处理。

有下列行为之一的,由公安机关交通管理部门处二百元以上二千元以下罚款:

(一)未取得机动车驾驶证、机动车驾驶证被吊销或者机动车驾驶证被暂扣期间驾驶机动车的;

(二)将机动车交由未取得机动车驾驶证或者机动车驾驶证被吊销、暂扣的人驾驶的;

(三)造成交通事故后逃逸,尚不构成犯罪的;

(四)机动车行驶超过规定时速百分之五十的;

(五)强迫机动车驾驶人违反道路交通安全法律、法规和机动车安全驾驶要求驾驶机动车,造成交通事故,尚不构成犯罪的;

(六)违反交通管制的规定强行通行,不听劝阻的;

(七)故意损毁、移动、涂改交通设施,造成危害后果,尚不构成犯罪的;

(八)非法拦截、扣留机动车辆,不听劝阻,造成交通严重阻塞或者较大财产损失的。

行为人有前款第二项、第四项情形之一的,可以并处吊销机动车驾驶证;有第一项、第三项、第五项至第八项情形之一的,可以并处十五日以下拘留。

law_content:
If the party fails to fulfill the administrative penalty decision within the prescribed time limit, the administrative organ that issued the administrative penalty decision may take the following measures:

(1) In case of failure to pay the fine upon expiration, a penalty of 3% of the amount of the fine shall be added daily;

(2) Apply for compulsory enforcement by the people's court.

zh_law_content:
当事人逾期不履行行政处罚决定的,作出行政处罚决定的行政机关可以采取下列措施:

(一)到期不缴纳罚款的,每日按罚款数额的百分之三加处罚款;

(二)申请人民法院强制执行。

law_content:
Traffic police shall be given administrative sanctions in accordance with the law for one of the following behaviors:

(1) Issuing registration certificates, number plates, driving licenses, and inspection marks to motor vehicles that do not meet the statutory conditions;

(2) Approving the installation and use of sirens, warning lights, and spray-painted logos on police cars, fire trucks, ambulances, and engineering rescue vehicles that do not meet the statutory conditions;

(3) Issuing driving licenses to individuals who do not meet the driving permit requirements, have not taken the examination, or have failed the examination;

(4) Failing to implement the system of separating the imposition of fines from the collection of fines or not depositing all lawfully collected fees, fines, and confiscated illegal gains into the national treasury as required;

(5) Organizing or participating in the operation of driving schools, driving training classes, motor vehicle repair shops, or paid parking lots, etc.;

(6) Accepting bribes or seeking other personal interests using one's position;

(7) Illegally seizing vehicles, motor vehicle driving licenses, driving licenses, and vehicle number plates;

(8) Using vehicles that have been legally seized;

(9) Collecting fines on the spot without issuing a receipt or falsifying the fine amount;

(10) Engaging in misconduct or improper handling of traffic accidents;

(11) Deliberately causing difficulties and delaying the processing of motor vehicle license plates;

(12) Using sirens and warning lights when not on an emergency mission;

(13) Violating regulations by intercepting and inspecting vehicles that are driving normally;

(14) Intercepting persons boarding motor vehicles when not on an emergency official duty;

(15) Failing to fulfill statutory duties.

The traffic management department of the public security organ shall have the authority specified in the preceding paragraph.

zh_law_content:
交通警察有下列行为之一的,依法给予行政处分:

(一)为不符合法定条件的机动车发放机动车登记证书、号牌、行驶证、检验合格标志的;

(二)批准不符合法定条件的机动车安装、使用警车、消防车、救护车、工程救险车的警报器、标志灯具,喷涂标志图案的;

(三)为不符合驾驶许可条件、未经考试或者考试不合格人员发放机动车驾驶证的;

(四)不执行罚款决定与罚款收缴分离制度或者不按规定将依法收取的费用、收缴的罚款及没收的违法所得全部上缴国库的;

(五)举办或者参与举办驾驶学校或者驾驶培训班、机动车修理厂或者收费停车场等经营活动的;

(六)利用职务上的便利收受他人财物或者谋取其他利益的;

(七)违法扣留车辆、机动车行驶证、驾驶证、车辆号牌的;

(八)使用依法扣留的车辆的;

(九)当场收取罚款不开具罚款收据或者不如实填写罚款额的;

(十)徇私舞弊,不公正处理交通事故的;

(十一)故意刁难,拖延办理机动车牌证的;

(十二)非执行紧急任务时使用警报器、标志灯具的;

(十三)违反规定拦截、检查正常行驶的车辆的;

(十四)非执行紧急公务时拦截搭乘机动车的;

(十五)不履行法定职责的。

公安机关交通管理部门有前款所列行为之一的,对直接负责的主管人员和其他直接责任人员给予相应的行政处分。

law_content:
The operator sells goods through methods such as the internet, television, telephone, and mail order. Consumers have the right to return the goods within seven days from the date of receipt, without providing any reasons, but the following goods are excluded:

(1) Goods customized by consumers;

(2) Perishable goods;

(3) Digitized goods such as online downloads or audiovisual products and computer software that have been opened by consumers;

(4) Delivered newspapers and periodicals.

Except for the goods listed above, other goods that are not suitable for return due to their nature and confirmed by consumers at the time of purchase are not eligible for a no-reason return.

The goods returned by consumers should be in good condition. The operator should refund the consumer the purchase price of the goods within seven days from the date of receiving the returned goods. The shipping costs of the returned goods are borne by the consumer; if there is an agreement between the operator and the consumer, it shall be in accordance with the agreement.

Consumer associations perform the following public welfare responsibilities:

(1) Provide consumers with consumption information and advisory services, enhance consumers' ability to protect their legitimate rights and interests, and guide civilized, healthy, resource-saving, and environmentally friendly consumption patterns;

(2) Participate in the formulation of laws, regulations, rules, and mandatory standards related to consumer rights and interests;

(3) Participate in the supervision and inspection of goods and services by relevant administrative departments;

(4) Reflect on and query relevant departments regarding issues related to consumers' legitimate rights and interests, and make suggestions;

(5) Accept consumer complaints and investigate and mediate the issues raised;

(6) In cases where complaints involve product and service quality issues, qualified appraisers may be commissioned for assessment, and the appraisers should inform their opinions;

(7) Support consumers who have suffered losses to file lawsuits or lawsuits in accordance with this law against actions that harm consumer rights and interests;

(8) Expose and criticize actions that harm consumer rights and interests through mass media.

Governments at all levels should provide necessary support in terms of funds and other support for consumer associations in performing their duties.

Consumer associations should fulfill their responsibilities to protect consumers' legitimate rights and interests, listen to consumers' opinions and suggestions, and accept social supervision.

Other consumer organizations established in accordance with the law shall carry out activities to protect consumers' legitimate rights and interests in accordance with the provisions of laws, regulations, and their articles of association.

Consumers and operators who have disputes over consumer rights and interests can resolve them through the following channels:

(1) Negotiation and settlement with the operator;
(2) Request mediation from consumer associations or other legally established mediation organizations;
(3) File a complaint with relevant administrative departments;
(4) Submit the dispute to an arbitration institution based on an arbitration agreement reached with the operator;
(5) File a lawsuit with a people's court.

If the operator provides goods or services with any of the following circumstances, except as provided by this law, they shall bear civil liability in accordance with the relevant laws and regulations:

(1) Goods or services have defects;

(2) Goods sold without indicating the necessary performance they should possess;

(3) Goods do not conform to the specified standards indicated on the goods or their packaging;

(4) Goods do not meet the quality conditions indicated in the product description or physical samples;

(5) Goods that have been phased out by the country or have become ineffective or spoiled;

(6) Insufficient quantity of goods sold;

(7) Services that do not comply with the agreed content and fees;

(8) Deliberately delay or unreasonably refuse consumer's requests for repair, remake, replacement, return, supplement of goods quantity, refund of payment and service fees, or compensation for losses;

(9) Other situations specified by laws and regulations that damage consumer rights and interests.

If the operator fails to fulfill the safety guarantee obligations to the consumer and causes damage to the consumer, they shall bear liability for infringement.

If the operator falls into any of the following situations, in addition to assuming corresponding civil liability, if there are regulations on the punitive authority and the method of punishment in other relevant laws and regulations, they shall be enforced according to the provisions of the laws and regulations; if there are no regulations in the laws and regulations, the industrial and commercial administrative departments or other relevant administrative departments shall order correction and may impose a fine of one to ten times the illegal income, or a single fine, or a combination of warning, confiscation of illegal income, and a fine of less than five hundred thousand yuan if there is no illegal income; if the circumstances are serious, they shall be ordered to suspend business for rectification or revoke the business license:

(1) The provided goods or services do not meet the requirements for ensuring personal and property safety;

(2) Mixing, counterfeiting, substituting inferior products for good ones, or selling unqualified products as qualified products;

(3) Producing goods that have been explicitly phased out by the state or selling expired or deteriorated goods;

(4) Forging the origin of goods, counterfeiting or using other people's factory names or addresses, tampering with production dates, forging or using counterfeit quality marks or certification marks;

(5) Selling goods that should be inspected and quarantined without inspection or quarantine, or forging inspection and quarantine results;

(6) Making false or misleading advertisements for goods or services;

(7) Refusing or delaying the implementation of measures by relevant administrative departments to stop the sale, issue warning, recall, harmless treatment, destruction, suspension of production or services for defective goods or services;

(8) Failing to repair, remake, replace, return, supplement the quantity of goods, or refund the goods and service fees requested by consumers.

A labor contract shall be concluded in written form and include the following terms:

(1) Duration of the labor contract;

(2) Job responsibilities;

(3) Labor protection and working conditions;

(4) Remuneration for labor;

(5) Labor discipline;

(6) Conditions for termination of the labor contract;

(7) Liabilities for breach of the labor contract.

In addition to the essential terms specified in the preceding paragraph, the parties may negotiate and agree on other provisions.

The employer may terminate an employment contract if an employee meets any of the following circumstances:

(1) During the probation period, it is proven that the employee does not meet the conditions for employment;

(2) The employee seriously violates labor discipline or the employer's rules and regulations;

(3) The employee seriously neglects their duties, commits misconduct, and causes significant harm to the interests of the employer;

(4) The employee is legally held accountable for a criminal offence.

If an employee falls into any of the following circumstances, the employer shall not terminate the labor contract in accordance with the provisions of Article 26 and Article 27 of this Law:

(1) Suffering from an occupational disease or work-related injury and being confirmed to have lost or partially lost labor capacity;

(2) Being ill or injured and within the prescribed medical treatment period;

(3) Female employees during pregnancy, confinement, or lactation period;

(4) Other circumstances as provided by laws and administrative regulations.

In one of the following circumstances, the employee can notify the employer at any time to terminate the labor contract:

(1) During the probation period;

(2) The employer forces labor by violence, threats, or illegal restriction of personal freedom;

(3) The employer fails to pay labor remuneration or provide working conditions as agreed in the labor contract.

In case of any of the following circumstances, the employing unit shall pay wages higher than the normal working hours of the employee according to the following standards:

(1) If the employee is required to work overtime, the employing unit shall pay wages not less than 150% of the normal wages;

(2) If the employee is scheduled to work on a rest day and cannot arrange compensatory leave, the employing unit shall pay wages not less than 200% of the normal wages;

(3) If the employee is scheduled to work on a statutory holiday, the employing unit shall pay wages not less than 300% of the normal wages.

The determination and adjustment of the minimum wage standard should take into account the following factors:

(1) The minimum cost of living for workers and the average number of dependents;

(2) The average wage level in society;

(3) Labor productivity;

(4) Employment situation;

(5) Differences in economic development levels between regions.

Workers are entitled to social insurance benefits in the following situations:

(1) Retirement;

(2) Illness or injury;

(3) Disability or occupational disease;

(4) Unemployment;

(5) Maternity.

After the death of a worker, their dependents are entitled to survivor benefits in accordance with the law.

The conditions and standards for workers to enjoy social insurance benefits are stipulated by laws and regulations.

Social insurance benefits received by workers must be paid in full and on time.

If an employing unit infringes upon the legitimate rights and interests of a worker in any of the following circumstances, the labor administrative department shall order the employer to pay the worker's wages, economic compensation, and may also order the payment of damages:

(1) Deducting or arbitrarily withholding a worker's wages;

(2) Refusing to pay a worker's overtime wages;

(3) Paying a worker's wages below the local minimum wage standards;

(4) Failing to provide economic compensation to a worker in accordance with the provisions of this law after termination of the labor contract.

One of the following situations makes the marriage invalid:
(1) Bigamy;
(2) Marrying a close relative within the prohibited degree of kinship;
(3) Having a disease before marriage that is medically considered unfit for marriage, and is not yet cured after marriage;
(4) Marrying before reaching the legal age of marriage.

The following properties acquired by a married couple during the existence of their marriage shall be jointly owned by the couple:
(1) Wages and bonuses;
(2) Income from production and business activities;
(3) Income from intellectual property rights;
(4) Inherited or gifted properties, except as specified in Article 18(3) of this law;
(5) Other properties that should be jointly owned.

The couple shall have equal rights to deal with the jointly owned properties.

One of the following situations constitutes the property of one party of the couple:
(1) Pre-marital property of one party;
(2) Medical expenses, disability allowance, and other fees obtained by one party due to physical injury;
(3) Property specifically designated for one party according to a will or donation contract;
(4) Personal belongings exclusively used by one party;
(5) Other property that should belong to one party.

If one party requests a divorce, the relevant department can mediate or the party can directly file a divorce lawsuit with the people's court. The people's court shall mediate divorce cases and if the emotions are indeed broken and mediation is ineffective, the divorce shall be granted.

If one of the following circumstances applies and mediation is ineffective, the divorce shall be granted:
(1) Bigamy or cohabitation with another person while having a spouse;
(2) Committing domestic violence or maltreatment and abandoning family members;
(3) Having persistent bad habits such as gambling or drug abuse;
(4) Separation due to disharmony in emotions for more than two years;
(5) Other situations leading to the breakdown of the marital relationship.

If one party is declared missing and the other party files for divorce, the divorce shall be granted.

One of the following circumstances, which leads to divorce, allows the innocent party to request compensation for damages:
(1) Having committed bigamy;
(2) Cohabiting with someone other than the spouse;
(3) Committing domestic violence;
(4) Abusing or abandoning family members.

(Original 15 provisions) In the following circumstances, criminal liability shall not be pursued. If it has already been pursued, the case shall be withdrawn, or not prosecuted, or trial shall be terminated, or acquittal shall be pronounced:

(1) The circumstances are significantly minor and the harm is negligible, and it is not considered a crime;

(2) The statute of limitations for prosecution has expired;

(3) The punishment has been exempted by a special amnesty order;

(4) The crime is only subject to prosecution upon a complaint in accordance with the Criminal Law, and no complaint has been filed or the complaint has been withdrawn;

(5) The suspect or defendant of the crime has died;

(6) Other laws provide for exemption from criminal liability.

Translation:

In the aforementioned situations, if one of the following circumstances exist, criminal responsibility shall not be pursued. If it has already been pursued, the case shall be withdrawn, or not prosecuted, or trial shall be terminated, or acquittal shall be pronounced:

(1) The circumstances are significantly minor and the harm is negligible, and it is not considered a crime;

(2) The statute of limitations for prosecution has expired;

(3) The punishment has been exempted by a special amnesty order;

(4) The crime is only subject to prosecution upon a complaint in accordance with the Criminal Law, and no complaint has been filed or the complaint has been withdrawn;

(5) The suspect or defendant of the crime has died;

(6) Other laws provide for exemption from criminal liability.

Criminal cases under the jurisdiction of intermediate people's courts for the first instance include:

(1) Cases endangering national security and involving terrorist activities;

(2) Cases that may result in life imprisonment or death penalty.

(Original Article 28) If judges, prosecutors, or investigators have any of the following circumstances, they shall voluntarily recuse themselves, and the parties and their legal representatives are also entitled to request them to recuse themselves:

(1) They are a party to the case or a close relative of a party;

(2) They or their close relatives have an interest in the case;

(3) They have served as witnesses, appraisers, defense attorneys, or litigation agents in the case;

(4) They have other relationships with the parties involved in the case that may affect the fair handling of the case.

Translation:
If any of the following circumstances exist, judges, prosecutors, or investigators shall recuse themselves voluntarily, and the parties and their legal representatives have the right to request their recusal:

(1) They are a party to the case or a close relative of a party;

(2) They or their close relatives have a vested interest in the case;

(3) They have previously served as witnesses, appraisers, defense attorneys, or litigation agents in the case;

(4) They have other relationships with the parties involved in the case that may potentially impact the impartial handling of the case.

(The Original 32 Articles) In addition to exercising their own right to defense, criminal suspects and defendants may also entrust one or two persons to act as defense counsel. The following individuals may be entrusted as defense counsel:

1. Lawyers;
2. Individuals recommended by people's organizations or the unit where the criminal suspect or defendant is located;
3. The guardian, relatives, or friends of the criminal suspect or defendant.

Individuals who are currently serving sentences or who have been lawfully deprived or restricted of personal freedom may not serve as defense counsel.

Translation:

(Article 32) In addition to exercising their own right to defense, criminal suspects and defendants may also entrust one or two persons to act as defense counsel. The following individuals may be entrusted as defense counsel:

1. Lawyers;
2. Individuals recommended by people's organizations or the unit where the criminal suspect or defendant is located;
3. The guardian, relatives, or friends of the criminal suspect or defendant.

Individuals who are currently serving sentences or who have been lawfully deprived or restricted of personal freedom may not serve as defense counsel.

(Evidence)

Evidence that can be used to prove the facts of a case is referred to as evidence.

Evidence includes:

(1) Physical evidence; 
(2) Documentary evidence; 
(3) Testimony of witnesses; 
(4) Statements of victims; 
(5) Confessions and defenses of the suspect or defendant; 
(6) Expert opinions; 
(7) Records of investigation processes such as on-site inspection, examination, identification, and experimental investigation; 
(8) Audio-visual materials and electronic data.

Evidence must be verified as true before it can be used as a basis for a verdict.

(Original Article 46) in all cases, the judgment shall be based on evidence and rigorous investigation, and not easily rely on confessions. If there is only the defendant's confession without any other evidence, the defendant cannot be found guilty and sentenced; if there is no confession from the defendant but the evidence is reliable and sufficient, the defendant can be found guilty and sentenced.

The reliability and sufficiency of the evidence must meet the following conditions:

1. There is evidence to prove the facts of the conviction and sentencing;
2. The evidence used to close the case has been verified as true through legal procedures;
3. Based on a comprehensive consideration of all the evidence in the case, any reasonable doubt about the established facts has been eliminated.

In cases involving crimes that endanger national security, terrorist activities, organized crimes with mafia characteristics, drug crimes, etc., if witnesses, expert witnesses, or victims face personal safety risks due to testifying in court, the people's court, the people's procuratorate, and the public security organs shall take one or more of the following protective measures:

1. Not disclosing the real names, addresses, and workplaces of individuals;
2. Implementing measures to conceal appearance, true voice, etc. when testifying in court;
3. Prohibiting specific individuals from contacting witnesses, expert witnesses, victims, and their immediate relatives;
4. Implementing specialized protection measures for personal safety and residence;
5. Other necessary protective measures.

If witnesses, expert witnesses, or victims believe that they or their immediate relatives face personal safety risks due to testifying in court, they may request protection from the people's court, the people's procuratorate, or the public security organs.

The people's court, the people's procuratorate, and the public security organs shall take protective measures in accordance with the law, and relevant units and individuals shall cooperate. (This provision is newly added)

Article 51: A person who is a suspect or defendant in a criminal case may be released on bail pending trial by the people's court, procuratorate, or public security organ under any of the following circumstances:

(1) The person may be sentenced to a punishment of control, detention, or an additional punishment;

(2) The person may be sentenced to imprisonment for a fixed term or above, but bail would not pose a risk to society;

(3) A woman who has a serious illness, cannot take care of herself, is pregnant, or is breastfeeding her own infant, but bail would not pose a risk to society;

(4) The period of detention has expired, the case has not been concluded, and bail is necessary.

The granting of bail pending trial shall be implemented by the public security organ.

The guarantor must meet the following conditions:

(1) Not involved in the case in question;

(2) Capable of fulfilling the guarantee obligation;

(3) Enjoy political rights and personal freedom without any restrictions;

(4) Have a fixed residence and income.

(Crackdown of the 56)

Suspects and defendants who are released on bail pending trial shall abide by the following provisions:

(1) Without approval from the executing authority, they shall not leave the city or county where they reside;

(2) If there is a change in their address, workplace, or contact information, they shall report to the executing authority within twenty-four hours;

(3) They shall promptly appear in court when summoned;

(4) They shall not interfere with witnesses in any form;

(5) They shall not destroy, forge evidence, or collude in giving false testimony.

People's courts, procuratorates, and public security organs can, according to the circumstances of the case, order the suspects or defendants released on bail pending trial to comply with one or more of the following provisions:

(1) They shall not enter specific places;

(2) They shall not meet or communicate with specific individuals;

(3) They shall not engage in specific activities;

(4) They shall surrender their passport or other exit-entry documents, as well as driver's licenses, to the executing authority for safekeeping.

If suspects or defendants released on bail pending trial violate the provisions of the first two clauses, and they have deposited a security, the relevant authorities can confiscate all or part of the security, and, depending on the circumstances, order the suspects or defendants to repent, make a new deposit, provide a guarantor, or impose residential surveillance or arrest.

In cases where suspects or defendants violate the provisions of bail pending trial and require arrest, they can be placed under preliminary detention.

People's courts, procuratorates, and public security organs can impose residential surveillance on criminal suspects or defendants who meet the conditions for arrest and fall into one of the following situations:

（1）Those suffering from severe illness and unable to take care of themselves;

（2）Pregnant women or women who are breastfeeding their own infants;

（3）The sole caregiver of a person who cannot take care of themselves;

（4）Due to the special circumstances of the case or the need to handle the case, residential surveillance is more appropriate;

（5）The deadline for detention has expired, the case has not been concluded, and residential surveillance is needed.

Residential surveillance can also be imposed on criminal suspects or defendants who meet the conditions for release on bail pending trial, but are unable to provide a guarantor or pay a bail bond.

Residential surveillance is executed by the public security organs.

(Sixty Original Articles) If there is evidence to prove the existence of criminal facts and the suspect or defendant may be sentenced to imprisonment or a heavier punishment, arrest shall be carried out when it is insufficient to prevent the occurrence of the following social dangers:

(1) The possibility of committing new crimes;

(2) There is a real danger to national security, public safety, or social order;

(3) The possibility of destroying or falsifying evidence, interfering with witness testimony, or colluding in testimony;

(4) The possibility of retaliating against victims, informants, or accusers;

(5) The attempt to commit suicide or escape.

If there is evidence to prove the existence of criminal facts and the possible sentence is imprisonment for ten years or more, or if there is evidence to prove the existence of criminal facts and the possible sentence is imprisonment or a heavier punishment, and the intention to commit a crime or identity is unclear, arrest shall be carried out.

If a criminal suspect or defendant who is on bail pending trial or under residential surveillance violates the rules on bail or residential surveillance and the circumstances are serious, arrest can be carried out.

(Original Article 63) Any citizen has the right to immediately report to the public security organs, people's procuratorates, or people's courts in the following circumstances:

(1) If a person is committing a crime or is discovered immediately after committing a crime;

(2) If a person is on a wanted list;

(3) If a person has escaped from prison;

(4) If a person is being pursued.

Translation:
(Original Article 63) Any citizen has the right to immediately report to the public security organs, people's procuratorates, or people's courts in the following circumstances:

(1) If a person is in the act of committing a crime or is discovered immediately after committing a crime;

(2) If a person is wanted by the authorities;

(3) If a person has escaped from prison;

(4) If a person is being pursued.

The People's Procuratorate conducts questioning and approves arrests. The following circumstances require questioning of the criminal suspect:

(1) When there are doubts about whether the arrest conditions are met;

(2) When the criminal suspect requests to make a statement in person to the prosecutor;

(3) When the investigation activities may involve major illegal behavior.

The People's Procuratorate conducting the review and approval of arrests can also question witnesses and other participants in the litigation, and listen to the opinions of defense lawyers. If requested by defense lawyers, their opinions should be heard.

(81 original provisions) The meanings of the following terms under this Law are as follows:

(1) "investigation" refers to the specialized investigative work and related compulsory measures conducted by public security organs and people's procuratorates in the process of handling cases in accordance with the law;

(2) "party" refers to the victim, private prosecutor, criminal suspect, defendant, plaintiff and defendant in an incidental civil action;

(3) "legal representative" refers to the parents, adoptive parents, guardians and representatives of organizations or groups with protective responsibilities of the person being represented;

(4) "participant in litigation" refers to the party, legal representative, legal counsel, defense counsel, witness, appraiser, and translator;

(5) "legal counsel" refers to a person entrusted by the victim or their legal representative, or close relatives, in a public prosecution case, or a person entrusted by the private prosecutor or their legal representative in a private prosecution case, or a person entrusted by a party or their legal representative in an incidental civil action, to participate in the litigation;

(6) "close relatives" refers to spouses, parents, children, siblings, and siblings of the same parents.

Chapter 2 Filing, Investigation, and Prosecution

Section 1 Filing

(Original 90) The parties, defense counsel, litigation agents, and interested parties have the right to lodge complaints or file accusations against judicial authorities and their staff if they engage in any of the following behaviors:

(1) Failing to release, revoke, or modify mandatory measures upon the expiration of the statutory period;

(2) Failing to return the bail deposited for release pending trial;

(3) Imposing sealings, seizures, or freeze measures on property unrelated to the case;

(4) Failing to lift sealings, seizures, or freeze measures that should have been lifted;

(5) Embezzling, misappropriating, misallocating, swapping, or violating regulations in the use of sealed, seized, or frozen property.

The agency responsible for accepting complaints or accusations shall handle them promptly. If dissatisfied with the handling, appeals can be made to the people's procuratorate at the same level. For cases directly accepted by the people's procuratorate, appeals can be made to the higher-level people's procuratorate. The people's procuratorate shall promptly review the appeals, and if the situation is found to be true, the relevant agencies shall be notified to make corrections.

Section 2 Interrogation of Criminal Suspects.

(Clauses 126) In cases where the investigation cannot be concluded within the time limit specified in Article 154 of this Law, the period may be extended by two months with the approval or decision of the People's Procuratorate at the provincial, autonomous region, or directly governed municipality level, in the following circumstances:

(1) Major complex cases in remote areas with extremely inconvenient transportation;

(2) Major criminal group cases;

(3) Major complex cases involving continuous criminal activities;

(4) Major complex cases involving a wide range of crimes and difficulties in collecting evidence.

When reviewing a case, the People's Procuratorate must ascertain:

1. Whether the criminal facts and circumstances are clear, the evidence is reliable and sufficient, and the determination of the nature of the crime and the charges is correct;

2. Whether there are any omitted crimes and other individuals who should be held criminally responsible;

3. Whether it belongs to cases where criminal responsibility should not be pursued;

4. Whether there is any accompanying civil litigation;

5. Whether the investigative activities are lawful.

(162) After the final statement of the defendant, the presiding judge announces a recess, and the collegiate bench enters into deliberation. Based on the established facts, evidence, and relevant legal provisions, the following judgments are made:

(1) If the case facts are clear, the evidence is credible and sufficient, and according to the law, the defendant is deemed guilty, a guilty judgment shall be rendered;

(2) If according to the law, the defendant is deemed not guilty, an acquittal judgment shall be rendered;

(3) If the evidence is insufficient to establish the guilt of the defendant, a not guilty judgment shall be rendered on the grounds of insufficient evidence and the inability to establish the alleged crime.

Please translate the above content into English.

(Original 165) During the court trial, if any of the following situations occur and affect the progress of the trial, it may be postponed:

(1) The need to notify new witnesses to appear in court, obtain new physical evidence, or conduct re-evaluations or inspections;

(2) The prosecutor discovers that supplementary investigations are required in the case being prosecuted and makes recommendations;

(3) The trial cannot proceed due to an application for recusal.

Please translate the above content into English:

(165 Revised) During the course of a court trial, if any of the following circumstances arise and affect the progress of the trial, it may be adjourned:

(1) The need to notify new witnesses to appear in court, obtain new physical evidence, or conduct re-examinations or on-site inspections;

(2) The prosecutor discovers the need for additional investigation in the case being prosecuted and makes recommendations;

(3) The trial cannot proceed due to a recusal application.

In the trial process, if any of the following circumstances occur, causing the case to be unable to continue for a long time, the trial may be suspended:

(1) The defendant suffers from a serious illness and cannot appear in court;

(2) The defendant escapes;

(3) The private prosecutor suffers from a serious illness and cannot appear in court, without appointing a legal representative to appear;

(4) Due to irresistible reasons.

After the reason for the suspension of the trial disappears, the trial should be resumed. The period of suspension of the trial does not count towards the trial period.

(Original 170 clauses) Self-prosecution cases include the following cases:

(1) Cases that are only handled upon complaint;

(2) Minor criminal cases where the victim has evidence to prove the offense;

(3) Cases where the victim has evidence to prove that the defendant has infringed upon their personal or property rights, but the public security organs or the people's procuratorate do not prosecute the defendant for criminal responsibility.

Translation:

(1) Cases that are only handled upon complaint;

(2) Minor criminal cases where the victim has evidence to prove the offense;

(3) Cases where the victim has evidence to prove that the defendant has infringed upon their personal or property rights, but the public security organs or the people's procuratorate do not prosecute the defendant for criminal responsibility.

One of the following situations is not applicable to summary proceedings:

(1) The defendant is blind, deaf, mute, or has not completely lost the ability to discern or control their own behavior as a mentally ill person;

(2) It has significant social impact;

(3) In joint criminal cases, some defendants do not plead guilty or have objections to the application of summary proceedings;

(4) Other cases that are not suitable for summary proceedings.

Translation:
One of the following situations is not applicable to summary proceedings:

(1) The defendant is blind, deaf, mute, or has not completely lost the ability to discern or control their own behavior as a mentally ill person;

(2) It has significant social impact;

(3) In joint criminal cases, some defendants do not plead guilty or have objections to the application of summary proceedings;

(4) Other cases that are not suitable for summary proceedings.

The second instance people's court shall form a collegial panel and hold a court session to hear the following cases:

(1) Appeals that may affect the conviction and sentencing due to objections raised by the defendant, private prosecutor, or their legal representatives against the facts and evidence determined in the first instance trial;

(2) Appeals against death penalty sentences imposed on the defendant;

(3) Cases appealed by the People's Procuratorate;

(4) Other cases that should be heard in a court session.

If the second instance people's court decides not to hold a court session, the defendant shall be interrogated, and the opinions of other parties, defense lawyers, and litigation agents shall be heard.

The second instance people's court may hold a court session for the appeals and cases appealed by the People's Procuratorate in the place where the case occurred or the place where the original instance people's court is located.

(Original 189) The second-instance people's court shall handle appeals and protests against the first-instance judgments as follows after the review:

(1) If the original judgment accurately establishes the facts, correctly applies the law, and imposes an appropriate sentence, the appeal or protest shall be dismissed, and the original judgment shall be upheld;

(2) If the original judgment establishes the facts accurately but applies the law incorrectly or imposes an improper sentence, a new judgment shall be rendered;

(3) If the original judgment has unclear facts or insufficient evidence, the case may be re-judged after clarifying the facts. Alternatively, the original judgment may be revoked, and the case shall be remanded to the original trial people's court for retrial.

After the original trial people's court renders a judgment according to the provisions of the preceding paragraph, if the defendant files an appeal or the People's Procuratorate files a protest, the second-instance people's court shall make a judgment or ruling in accordance with the law and shall not remand the case for retrial to the original trial people's court.

If the second-instance people's court finds that the first-instance people's court has violated one of the following procedural violations of the law in the trial, it shall decide to revoke the original judgment and remand the case to the original trial people's court for retrial:

(1) Violating the provisions of this Law on public trials;

(2) Violating the system of avoidance;

(3) Depriving or restricting the litigant's statutory litigation rights, which may affect the fair trial;

(4) The composition of the trial organization is illegal;

(5) Other violations of legal procedures that may affect fair trial.

(Article 204) If the appeal of the party concerned, their legal representative, or close relatives meets one of the following circumstances, the people's court shall retry the case:

(1) There is new evidence to prove that the facts determined in the original judgment or ruling are erroneous, which may affect the conviction and sentencing;

(2) The evidence used for conviction and sentencing is not reliable or sufficient, which should be excluded according to law, or there is a contradiction between the main evidence proving the facts of the case;

(3) There is an error in the application of law in the original judgment or ruling;

(4) Violation of the legal procedures that may affect a fair trial;

(5) The presiding judge or trial personnel involved in the case were involved in corruption, bribery, or other misconduct in the trial process.

(Judgments and rulings shall be enforced after they have the force of law.

The following are judgments and rulings that have the force of law:

(1) Judgments and rulings that have not been appealed or protested within the statutory time limit;

(2) Final judgments and rulings;

(3) Death penalty judgments approved by the Supreme People's Court and death penalty judgments with a two-year suspension of execution approved by higher people's courts.)

(Under Article 211) After receiving the order from the Supreme People's Court to carry out the death penalty, the lower people's court shall execute it within seven days. However, if any of the following circumstances are discovered, the execution shall be suspended and immediately reported to the Supreme People's Court, which shall make a ruling:

(1) It is found before execution that there may be an error in the judgment;

(2) Before execution, the convict discloses significant criminal facts or has other significant acts of meritorious service, which may require a change in verdict;

(3) The convict is pregnant.

After the reasons for suspension under the preceding paragraphs (1) and (2) cease to exist, the execution can only be carried out upon obtaining the reissued order for execution from the President of the Supreme People's Court; for suspension due to the reason in the preceding paragraph (3), it shall be reported to the Supreme People's Court for lawful retrial.

Translation:

The types of penalties for public security administration include:

(1) Warning;

(2) Fine;

(3) Administrative detention;

(4) Revoking the permit issued by the public security organ.

For foreign nationals who violate public security administration, additional measures such as imposing a time limit for exiting the country or expulsion may be applied.

If any of the following circumstances occur in violation of public security management, the punishment shall be mitigated or not imposed:

(1) The circumstances are extremely minor;

(2) Actively eliminate or reduce the consequences of the violation and obtain forgiveness from the victim;

(3) Due to being coerced or deceived by others;

(4) Actively surrender, truthfully state their illegal acts to the public security organs;

(5) Having performed meritorious deeds.

Translate the above content into English: 

If any of the following circumstances occur, the punishment for violating public security management shall be mitigated or not imposed:

(1) The circumstances are particularly minor;

(2) Taking active measures to eliminate or reduce the consequences of the violation and obtaining forgiveness from the injured party;

(3) Acting under coercion or deception by others;

(4) Voluntarily surrendering and truthfully confessing one's illegal acts to the public security organs;

(5) Having made meritorious contributions.

In case of any of the following circumstances violating public security management, the punishment shall be severe:

(1) Having serious consequences;

(2) Inciting, coercing, or deceiving others to violate public security management;

(3) Engaging in retaliation against the reporter, accuser, whistleblower, or witness;

(4) Having received a public security management punishment within six months.

Those who violate public security management and fall into one of the following situations shall be subject to administrative detention punishment according to this law but not executed:

(1) Those who are over fourteen years old but under sixteen years old;

(2) Those who are over sixteen years old but under eighteen years old and violate public security management for the first time;

(3) Those who are over seventy years old;

(4) Those who are pregnant or breastfeeding an infant under one year old.

Anyone who commits any of the following acts shall be given a warning or fined up to 200 yuan; for more serious cases, they shall be detained for a period of at least five days but not more than ten days, and may also be fined up to 500 yuan:

(1) Disturbing the order of government agencies, organizations, enterprises, or institutions, resulting in the inability to carry out normal work, production, business, medical services, teaching, or scientific research, without causing serious losses;

(2) Disturbing the order of train stations, ports, docks, airports, shopping malls, parks, exhibition halls, or other public places;

(3) Disturbing the order on public buses, trams, trains, ships, aircraft, or other public transportation;

(4) Illegally intercepting, forcibly boarding, clinging to motor vehicles, ships, aircraft, or other means of transportation that impede the normal operation of the vehicles;

(5) Damaging the order of elections conducted in accordance with the law.

If the above acts are committed by a group, the principal offender shall be detained for a period of at least ten days but not more than fifteen days, and may also be fined up to 1,000 yuan.

Anyone who engages in any of the following behaviors that disrupt the order of large-scale mass activities such as culture or sports events shall be given a warning or a fine of up to 200 yuan; those with serious circumstances shall be detained for more than five days but less than ten days, and may also be fined up to 500 yuan:

(1) Forcibly entering the venue;
(2) Violating regulations by setting off fireworks, firecrackers, or other items within the venue;
(3) Displaying insulting slogans, banners, or other items;
(4) Surrounding and attacking referees, athletes, or other staff members;
(5) Throwing debris into the venue and refusing to stop;
(6) Engaging in other behaviors that disturb the order of large-scale mass activities.

Individuals who are detained for disrupting the order of sports events may also be banned from entering sports venues to watch similar events for a period of twelve months. Those who violate this regulation and enter sports venues shall be forcefully removed from the scene.

Those who engage in any of the following behaviors shall be subject to detention for a period of more than five days but less than ten days, and may also be fined up to 500 yuan; those who commit less serious acts shall be subject to detention for a period of less than five days or fined up to 500 yuan:

(1) Spreading rumors, falsely reporting dangerous situations, epidemics, police incidents, or intentionally disrupting public order by other means;

(2) Disrupting public order by releasing false explosive, toxic, radioactive, corrosive substances, or infectious disease pathogens;

(3) Threatening to commit arson, bombings, or releasing dangerous substances to disrupt public order;

(4) Stealing, damaging, or moving railway facilities, equipment, locomotives, vehicle components, or safety signs without authorization;

(5) Placing obstacles on railway tracks or intentionally throwing objects at trains;

(6) Digging pits, quarrying, or taking sand from railway tracks, bridges, or culverts;

(7) Illegally establishing road crossings or level crossings on railway tracks.

