Inheritance refers to the personal legal property left by a citizen upon their death, including:
(1) Citizen's income;
(2) Citizen's houses, savings, and personal belongings;
(3) Citizen's forests, livestock, and poultry;
(4) Citizen's cultural relics and books;
(5) Production means permitted by law for citizens' ownership;
(6) Property rights in citizens' copyrights and patent rights;
(7) Citizen's other lawful property.

The inheritor shall forfeit the right to inheritance if he or she engages in one of the following actions:

(1) Intentionally killing the decedent;
(2) Killing other inheritors in order to compete for the inheritance;
(3) Abandoning the decedent or subjecting the decedent to severe abuse;
(4) Forgery, alteration, or destruction of the will, with severe circumstances.

The following individuals cannot act as witnesses to a will:
(1) Persons without capacity or with restricted capacity for action;
(2) Heirs or recipients of legacies;
(3) Persons who have an interest in relation to the heirs or recipients of legacies.

The relevant part of the inheritance shall be handled according to statutory inheritance in the following cases:
(1) If the heir designated in the will renounces the inheritance or the beneficiary renounces the bequest;
(2) If the heir designated in the will loses the right of inheritance;
(3) If the heir designated in the will or the beneficiary dies before the testator;
(4) If the inheritance referred to in the invalid part of the will is involved;
(5) If the estate not disposed of in the will.

以上内容的英文翻译为:

In case of any of the following situations, the relevant part of the inheritance shall be handled according to statutory inheritance:
(1) The heir designated in the will renounces the inheritance or the beneficiary renounces the bequest.
(2) The heir designated in the will loses the right of inheritance.
(3) The heir designated in the will or the beneficiary dies before the testator.
(4) The inheritance referred to in the invalid part of the will is involved.
(5) The estate not disposed of in the will.

An open-ended labor contract refers to a labor contract between an employer and an employee that does not have a fixed termination date.

An employer and an employee can agree to enter into an open-ended labor contract through mutual negotiation. If any of the following circumstances occur and the employee proposes or agrees to renew or enter into a new labor contract, except when the employee proposes to enter into a fixed-term labor contract, an open-ended labor contract should be entered into:

1. The employee has worked continuously for ten years in the same employer;

2. When an employer implements the labor contract system for the first time or when a state-owned enterprise renews the labor contract after restructuring, the employee has worked continuously for ten years and is less than ten years away from the legal retirement age;

3. The labor contract has been renewed twice in a row, and the employee does not fall under the circumstances specified in Article 39 and Article 40, paragraph 1 and paragraph 2 of this law.

If an employer fails to enter into a written labor contract with an employee within one year from the start of the employment, it shall be deemed that the employer and the employee have entered into an open-ended labor contract.

The labor contract should include the following clauses:

(1) Name, address, and legal representative or main person in charge of the employer;

(2) Name, address, and resident identity card or other valid identity document number of the worker;

(3) Duration of the labor contract;

(4) Job responsibilities and work location;

(5) Working hours and rest days;

(6) Remuneration;

(7) Social insurance;

(8) Labor protection, working conditions, and occupational hazard prevention;

(9) Other matters that should be included in the labor contract according to laws and regulations.

In addition to the mandatory clauses mentioned above, the employer and the worker can also agree on other matters such as probation period, training, confidentiality, supplementary insurance, and welfare benefits.

In the event of any of the following circumstances, the employer may terminate the labor contract by giving the employee a written notice thirty days in advance or by paying the employee an additional month's salary:

(1) If the employee becomes sick or is non-work-related injured and is unable to perform their original job duties after the prescribed medical treatment period, and the employer cannot arrange alternative work for them;

(2) If the employee is unable to perform their job duties even after training or job reassignment;

(3) If there is a significant change in the objective circumstances on which the labor contract was based, making it impossible to fulfill the labor contract, and the employer and employee fail to reach an agreement on amending the contract.

If any of the following circumstances occur, which require a reduction of personnel by more than twenty people or a reduction of less than twenty people but accounting for more than ten percent of the total number of employees in the enterprise, the employer shall explain the situation to the trade union or all employees, listen to the opinions of the trade union or employees, and report the personnel reduction plan to the labor administration department after approval, the personnel reduction may be carried out:

(1) Reorganization in accordance with the Enterprise Bankruptcy Law;

(2) Significant difficulties in production and operation;

(3) Transferring production, major technological innovation, or adjusting the mode of operation, resulting in the need to reduce personnel even after changing labor contracts;

(4) Other major changes in the objective economic situation on which the labor contract was based, making it impossible to perform the labor contract.

When reducing personnel, the following individuals should be given priority for retention:

(1) Individuals with fixed-term labor contracts that have been concluded with the company for a relatively long period;

(2) Individuals with labor contracts that have no fixed term with the company;

(3) Individuals who have no other employed family members and have elderly or underage dependents.

If an employer, in accordance with the provisions of the first paragraph of this article, reduces personnel and hires new employees within six months, the employees who have been laid off should be informed, and the laid-off employees should be given priority for reemployment under the same conditions.

If one of the following circumstances applies to the employee, the employer shall not terminate the labor contract in accordance with the provisions of Article 40 and Article 41 of this Law:

(1) The employee engaged in occupational disease hazard operations did not undergo occupational health examination before leaving the job, or suspected occupational disease patients during the diagnosis or medical observation period;

(2) The employee suffered from occupational diseases or partial or total loss of labor capacity due to work-related injuries and was confirmed;

(3) The employee is sick or not due to work-related injuries during the prescribed medical treatment period;

(4) Female employees during pregnancy, childbirth, or lactation;

(5) The employee has worked continuously in the same unit for fifteen years and is less than five years away from the legal retirement age;

(6) Other circumstances prescribed by laws and administrative regulations.

The termination of a labor contract shall occur in one of the following circumstances:

(1) The expiration of the term of the labor contract;

(2) The commencement of the lawful enjoyment of basic pension insurance benefits by the employee;

(3) The death of the employee or the employee being declared dead or missing by a people's court;

(4) The employer being declared bankrupt in accordance with the law;

(5) The revocation of the business license of the employer, the order to close or revoke the employer, or the decision by the employer to dissolve in advance;

(6) Other circumstances as stipulated by laws and administrative regulations.

The employer shall provide economic compensation to the employee in the following circumstances:

1. When the employee terminates the labor contract according to Article 38 of this Law;
2. When the employer proposes to terminate the labor contract according to Article 36 of this Law and reaches an agreement with the employee to terminate the labor contract;
3. When the employer terminates the labor contract according to Article 40 of this Law;
4. When the employer terminates the labor contract according to the first paragraph of Article 41 of this Law;
5. When the employer terminates the fixed-term labor contract according to the first provision of Article 44 of this Law, unless the employer maintains or improves the conditions of the labor contract and the employee does not agree to its renewal;
6. When the labor contract is terminated according to the fourth or fifth provision of Article 44 of this Law;
7. Other circumstances as provided by laws and administrative regulations.

The operation of labor dispatch services shall meet the following conditions:

(1) The registered capital shall not be less than RMB 2 million;

(2) There should be a fixed place of business and facilities suitable for conducting the business;

(3) There should be a labor dispatch management system in accordance with the laws and administrative regulations;

(4) Other conditions stipulated by laws and administrative regulations.

To operate labor dispatch services, an application for administrative licensing shall be submitted to the labor administrative department in accordance with the law. Upon approval, the corresponding company registration shall be processed in accordance with the law. Without permission, no unit or individual shall engage in labor dispatch services.

The employing unit shall fulfill the following obligations:

(1) Comply with national labor standards and provide corresponding working conditions and labor protection;

(2) Inform the dispatched workers of their job requirements and remuneration;

(3) Pay overtime wages, performance bonuses, and provide welfare benefits related to the job position;

(4) Provide necessary training for the dispatched workers on the job position;

(5) Implement a normal wage adjustment mechanism for continuous employment.

The employing unit shall not further dispatch the dispatched workers to other employers.

The labor administration departments of local people's governments at or above the county level shall supervise and inspect the following situations related to the implementation of the labor contract system:

(1) The formulation of rules and regulations by employers directly affecting the vital interests of workers and the implementation of such rules and regulations;

(2) The conclusion and termination of labor contracts between employers and workers;

(3) Compliance of labor dispatching units and employers with relevant regulations on labor dispatching;

(4) Compliance of employers with national regulations on working hours, rest and leave for workers;

(5) Payment of labor remuneration stipulated in labor contracts and compliance with minimum wage standards by employers;

(6) Participation of employers in various social insurances and payment of social insurance premiums;

(7) Other labor inspection matters stipulated by laws and regulations.

Employers who fall into any of the following situations shall be ordered by the labor administration department to pay labor remuneration, overtime pay, or economic compensation within a specified period of time; if the labor remuneration is lower than the local minimum wage standard, the difference shall be paid; if payment is overdue, the employer shall be ordered to pay additional compensation to the worker at a rate of no less than 50 percent and no more than 100 percent of the amount due:

(1) Failure to timely and fully pay the labor remuneration to workers as stipulated in the labor contract or national regulations;

(2) Payment of wages to workers below the local minimum wage standard;

(3) Failure to pay overtime wages for arranging overtime work;

(4) Failure to pay economic compensation to workers upon termination or rescission of the labor contract in accordance with the provisions of this Law.

Employers who are found to have committed any of the following acts shall be subject to administrative sanctions in accordance with the law; if their actions constitute a crime, they shall be held criminally liable; and if they cause harm to employees, they shall be responsible for compensation:

(1) Using violence, threats or illegal restrictions on personal freedom to force labor;

(2) Commanding work in violation of regulations or forcing workers to engage in hazardous operations that endanger their personal safety;

(3) Insulting, corporal punishment, beating, illegal search, or detention of workers;

(4) Providing harsh working conditions or causing severe environmental pollution that seriously damages the physical and mental health of workers.

Intermediate People's Courts have jurisdiction over the following types of civil cases as the court of first instance:
(1) Major foreign-related cases;
(2) Cases with significant impact within their jurisdiction;
(3) Cases determined by the Supreme People's Court to be under the jurisdiction of the Intermediate People's Court.

The following civil lawsuits shall be under the jurisdiction of the people's court in the domicile of the plaintiff; if the domicile of the plaintiff is different from the habitual residence, it shall be under the jurisdiction of the people's court in the habitual residence:
(1) Lawsuits related to identity disputes against individuals who do not reside within the territory of the People's Republic of China;
(2) Lawsuits related to identity disputes against individuals who are missing or declared missing;
(3) Lawsuits against individuals who are subject to compulsory education measures;
(4) Lawsuits against individuals who are imprisoned.

The following cases shall be exclusively under the jurisdiction of the People's Court as prescribed in this article:
(1) Lawsuits related to real estate disputes shall be under the jurisdiction of the People's Court in the location where the real estate is situated;
(2) Lawsuits arising from disputes occurring in port operations shall be under the jurisdiction of the People's Court in the location of the port;
(3) Lawsuits related to inheritance disputes shall be under the jurisdiction of the People's Court in the deceased's domicile at the time of death or the location where the main inheritance is situated.

The parties or their legal representatives may appoint one or two persons as attorneys for litigation.
The following individuals may be entrusted as attorneys for litigation:
(1) Lawyers and grassroots legal service workers;
(2) Relatives or employees of the parties;
(3) Citizens recommended by the community, organization, or relevant social groups where the parties are located.

The evidence includes:
(1) Statements of the parties involved;
(2) Documentary evidence;
(3) Physical evidence;
(4) Audiovisual materials;
(5) Electronic data;
(6) Testimony of witnesses;
(7) Expert opinions;
(8) Inspection records.
Evidence must be verified before it can be used as the basis for determining facts.

According to the notice from the People's Court, witnesses are required to appear in court to testify. However, with the permission of the People's Court, witnesses can provide testimony through written statements, audiovisual transmission technology, or audiovisual materials in the following situations:

(1) Inability to appear in court due to health reasons;
(2) Inability to appear in court due to long distance or transportation inconvenience;
(3) Inability to appear in court due to natural disasters or other force majeure circumstances;
(4) Other legitimate reasons for the inability to appear in court.

The People's Court is not required to prepare a mediation agreement in the following cases:
(1) Divorce cases that have been successfully mediated and settled;
(2) Cases involving the mediation and maintenance of adoption relationships;
(3) Cases that can be immediately executed;
(4) Other cases that do not require the preparation of a mediation agreement.

For agreements that do not require the preparation of a mediation agreement, they should be recorded in the minutes and signed or sealed by both parties, the presiding judge, and the court clerk, thereby obtaining legal effect.

The people's court, based on the parties' application, may rule for provisional execution in the following cases:
(1) Reclaiming alimony, support fees, nurturing fees, pension, and medical expenses;
(2) Reclaiming labor remuneration; 
(3) Cases that require immediate provisional execution due to urgent circumstances.

If any participant in a lawsuit or other person engages in any of the following behaviors, the people's court may impose fines or detention according to the severity of the circumstances; if it constitutes a crime, criminal responsibilities shall be pursued in accordance with the law:

(1) Falsifying or destroying important evidence, obstructing the people's court from hearing a case;
(2) Using violence, threats, or bribery to obstruct witnesses from testifying, or instructing, bribing, or coercing others to make false testimony;
(3) Concealing, transferring, selling, or damaging property that has been sealed or seized, or transferring property that has been frozen after being checked and ordered to be kept;
(4) Insulting, defaming, slandering, assaulting, or retaliating against judicial personnel, participants in litigation, witnesses, interpreters, appraisers, investigators, or persons assisting in enforcement;
(5) Using violence, threats, or other methods to obstruct judicial personnel from performing their duties;
(6) Refusing to abide by legally effective judgments or rulings of the people's court.

The people's court may impose fines or detention on the responsible person or directly responsible personnel of a unit that has engaged in any of the acts specified in the preceding paragraph; if it constitutes a crime, criminal responsibilities shall be pursued in accordance with the law.

If a unit with the obligation to assist in investigation and enforcement has one of the following behaviors, the people's court may, in addition to ordering it to fulfill its assistance obligation, impose a fine:

(1) Refusing or obstructing the investigation and evidence collection by the people's court;
(2) After receiving the notice of assistance in execution from the people's court, refusing to assist in the inquiry, seizure, freezing, transfer, or value change of property;
(3) After receiving the notice of assistance in execution from the people's court, refusing to assist in withholding the income of the executed person, handling the transfer procedures of relevant property rights certificates, transferring relevant tickets, certificates, or other properties;
(4) Other refusals to assist in the execution.

The people's court may impose a fine on the principal responsible person or directly responsible personnel of a unit that has one of the behaviors specified in the previous paragraph; and if the assistance obligation is still not fulfilled, the person may be subject to detention. The people's court may also make disciplinary recommendations to the supervisory organs or relevant authorities.

The people's court shall handle the following lawsuits as follows:

(1) If it falls within the scope of administrative proceedings under the Administrative Litigation Act, the plaintiff shall be informed to bring an administrative lawsuit;
(2) If both parties have reached a written arbitration agreement and are not allowed to file a lawsuit with the people's court according to the law, the plaintiff shall be informed to apply for arbitration with the arbitration institution;
(3) If the dispute should be handled by other authorities according to the law, the plaintiff shall be informed to apply to the relevant authority for resolution;
(4) For cases that do not fall under the jurisdiction of the court, the plaintiff shall be informed to file a lawsuit with the court having jurisdiction;
(5) For cases in which the judgment, ruling, or mediation agreement has obtained legal effect and the parties file a lawsuit again, the plaintiff shall be informed to apply for retrial, except when the people's court permits the withdrawal of the lawsuit;
(6) For cases that are not allowed to be filed within a certain period of time according to the law, if the lawsuit is filed within the prohibited period, it shall not be accepted;
(7) For divorce cases where the court refuses to grant a divorce or mediation reconciles the parties, and for adoption cases where the judgment or mediation maintains the adoption relationship, if there are no new circumstances or reasons, the plaintiff's lawsuit within six months shall not be accepted.

People's courts handle cases in the following ways:
(1) If the parties have no disputes and meet the requirements of the Summary Procedure, the case may be transferred to the Summary Procedure;
(2) If mediation is possible before the court hearing, the court takes mediation measures to promptly resolve the dispute;
(3) Based on the circumstances of the case, the court determines whether to apply the Simplified Procedure or the Ordinary Procedure;
(4) If a court hearing is necessary, the court clarifies the focus of the dispute by requesting the parties to exchange evidence, etc.

Section 3: Court Trial

The courtroom investigation is conducted in the following order:
(1) Statement by the parties involved;
(2) Informing witnesses of their rights and obligations, testimony from witnesses, and reading of testimonies from absent witnesses;
(3) Presentation of documentary evidence, physical evidence, audiovisual materials, and electronic data;
(4) Reading of expert opinions;
(5) Reading of the record of on-site investigation.

The courtroom debate is conducted in the following order:
(1) The plaintiff and their legal representative make their statements;
(2) The defendant and their legal representative present their defense;
(3) The third party and their legal representative make their statements or present their defense;
(4) Mutual debate.
After the courtroom debate concludes, the presiding judge solicits the final opinions of each party in the order of the plaintiff, defendant, and third party.

The trial can be postponed in any of the following circumstances:
(1) Where the parties and other participants who must appear in court have a legitimate reason for not appearing;
(2) Where a party submits a motion for recusal at the last minute;
(3) Where new witnesses need to be notified to appear in court, new evidence needs to be obtained, reexamination or inspection needs to be conducted, or additional investigation is required;
(4) Other circumstances where postponement is necessary.

The litigation shall be suspended in any of the following circumstances:
(1) One party to the litigation dies, and it is necessary to wait for the heir to express whether they will participate in the litigation;
(2) One party to the litigation loses litigation capacity and the legal representative has not been determined;
(3) The legal person or other organization that is one party to the litigation terminates, and the successor of rights and obligations has not been determined;
(4) One party to the litigation is unable to participate in the litigation due to irresistible reasons;
(5) This case must be based on the trial result of another case, which has not been concluded yet;
(6) Other circumstances where the litigation should be suspended.
Once the reasons for the suspension of litigation are eliminated, the litigation shall be resumed.

The judgment shall specify the judgment result and the reasons for making such judgment. The contents of the judgment shall include:

(1) The case, the claims in the litigation, the disputed facts, and the reasons;

(2) The facts and reasons identified in the judgment, the applicable laws and reasons;

(3) The judgment result and the burden of litigation costs;

(4) The appeal period and the court for appeal.

The judgment shall be signed by the judges and the court clerk, and stamped with the seal of the people's court.

The rulings applicable to the following scope are:

(1) Rejection of acceptance;
(2) Objections to jurisdiction;
(3) Dismissal of the lawsuit;
(4) Preservation and preliminary execution;
(5) Granting or refusing to withdraw the lawsuit;
(6) Suspending or terminating the litigation;
(7) Correcting clerical errors in the judgment;
(8) Suspending or terminating the execution;
(9) Revoking or refusing to enforce arbitration awards;
(10) Refusing to enforce notarial instruments with compulsory execution effect conferred by notary authorities;
(11) Other matters requiring rulings.

Rulings on items one to three of the preceding paragraph may be appealed.

The ruling shall state the result and the reasoning behind it. It shall be signed by the judge or clerk and sealed with the court's official stamp. If a ruling is made orally, it shall be recorded in the transcript.

The Second Instance People's Court shall handle the appeal cases as follows:

(1) If the original judgment or ruling has found the facts clear and applied the law correctly, the appeal shall be rejected by judgment or ruling, and the original judgment or ruling shall be upheld;

(2) If the original judgment or ruling has found the facts incorrect or applied the law erroneously, a new judgment or ruling shall be made in accordance with the law, or the original judgment or ruling shall be revoked or changed;

(3) If the original judgment has unclear basic facts, the original judgment shall be revoked by ruling and remanded to the original trial People's Court for retrial, or a new judgment shall be made after clarifying the facts;

(4) If the original judgment has seriously violated the statutory procedures by omitting the parties or issuing a judgment in violation of the law due to their absence, the original judgment shall be revoked by ruling and remanded to the original trial People's Court for retrial.

The Second Instance People's Court shall not remand the case for retrial again if the parties file an appeal against the judgment made by the original trial People's Court after its retrial.

