If the applicant meets one of the following circumstances, the people's court shall retry the case:

(1) There is new evidence sufficient to overturn the original judgment or ruling;

(2) The basic facts as determined by the original judgment or ruling lack evidence;

(3) The main evidence for determining the facts in the original judgment or ruling is forged;

(4) The main evidence for determining the facts in the original judgment or ruling has not been cross-examined;

(5) The party is unable to collect the main evidence necessary for the trial due to objective reasons and submits a written request to the people's court for investigation and collection, but the court fails to conduct the investigation and collection;

(6) There is a clear error in the application of the law in the original judgment or ruling;

(7) The composition of the trial organization is illegal or the judges who should have recused themselves did not do so in accordance with the law;

(8) A person without litigation capacity fails to be represented by a legal representative or a party who should participate in the litigation fails to do so due to circumstances beyond their control or their legal representative's control;

(9) The rights of the parties to debate are deprived in violation of the law;

(10) Absent judgment without being summoned by subpoena;

(11) The original judgment or ruling omits or exceeds the claims of the lawsuit;

(12) The legal document on which the original judgment or ruling was based has been revoked or changed;

(13) The judges involved in the trial have engaged in corrupt practices, bribery, or other acts of misconduct.

One of the following situations allows the parties concerned to apply for prosecutorial suggestions or appeals to the People's Procuratorate:

(1) When the people's court rejects the application for retrial;

(2) When the people's court fails to make a ruling on the application for retrial within the specified time limit;

(3) When the retrial judgment or ruling contains obvious errors.

The People's Procuratorate shall review the application of the parties concerned within three months and make a decision to propose prosecutorial suggestions or appeals or to reject the application. The parties concerned shall not apply for prosecutorial suggestions or appeals to the People's Procuratorate again.

The party who does not comply with the arbitration award of a lawfully established arbitration institution may apply for enforcement to the people's court with jurisdiction. The people's court receiving the application shall enforce it.
If the respondent presents evidence proving that the arbitration award falls under any of the following circumstances, the people's court, after review and verification by a panel of judges, shall rule not to enforce it:
(1) The parties did not include an arbitration clause in the contract or did not reach a written arbitration agreement afterwards;
(2) The matters ruled upon are not within the scope of the arbitration agreement or the arbitration institution does not have the authority to arbitrate;
(3) The composition of the arbitration tribunal or the arbitration procedure violated statutory procedures;
(4) The evidence on which the award is based is forged;
(5) The opposing party concealed evidence that could have an impact on a fair ruling from the arbitration institution;
(6) The arbitrator engaged in corruption, bribery, or other misconduct when arbitrating the case.
If the people's court determines that enforcing the award violates public interest, it shall rule not to enforce it.
The ruling shall be served on both parties and the arbitration institution.
If the arbitration award is ruled not to be enforced by the people's court, the party may reapply for arbitration based on the written arbitration agreement reached by both parties, or file a lawsuit with the people's court.

In any of the following circumstances, the people's court shall order the suspension of execution:
(1) The applicant represents that the execution can be postponed;
(2) A third party raises legitimate objections to the execution target;
(3) The death of a citizen who is a party requires waiting for the inheritance of rights or the assumption of obligations by the heir;
(4) The termination of a legal person or other organization that is a party, without the determination of the successor of rights and obligations;
(5) Other circumstances in which the people's court deems it necessary to suspend execution.
After the circumstances for suspension have disappeared, execution shall resume.

The people's court shall terminate the enforcement in the following cases:
(1) The applicant withdraws the application;
(2) The legal document on which the enforcement is based is revoked;
(3) The citizen who is the subject of enforcement dies without assets to be executed and without any obligation to bear;
(4) The right holder in a case of claiming alimony, support fees, or childcare fees dies;
(5) The citizen who is the subject of enforcement is unable to repay the loan due to living difficulties, has no source of income, and has lost the ability to work;
(6) Other circumstances in which the people's court considers it necessary to terminate the enforcement.

