If the respondent provides evidence to prove that one of the following circumstances exists with regard to the arbitration award made by the foreign-related arbitration institution of the People's Republic of China, the people's court, after examination and verification by a collegial panel, shall make a ruling not to enforce it:
(1) The parties did not include an arbitration clause in the contract, or did not reach a written arbitration agreement afterwards;
(2) The respondent did not receive a notification to appoint an arbitrator or to participate in the arbitration proceedings, or was unable to present its arguments due to reasons not attributable to the respondent;
(3) The composition of the arbitration tribunal or the arbitration procedure does not comply with the arbitration rules;
(4) The matters decided in the award do not fall within the scope of the arbitration agreement, or the arbitration institution does not have the authority to arbitrate on.
If the people's court determines that enforcing the award would violate the public interest, it shall make a ruling not to enforce it.

A mortgage contract shall include the following contents:
(1) Types and amounts of the secured principal claims;
(2) Term for the debtor to fulfill the obligations;
(3) Name, quantity, quality, condition, location, ownership or right of use of the mortgaged property;
(4) Scope of the mortgage guarantee;
(5) Other matters that the parties consider necessary to stipulate.

If a mortgage contract does not fully possess the above-mentioned contents, it may be rectified.

The following signs may not be used as trademarks:

(1) Identical or similar to the names, flags, emblems, anthems, military flags, military emblems, military songs, medals, etc. of the People's Republic of China, as well as the names, logos of central state organs, specific locations or landmark buildings, with similar graphics;

(2) Identical or similar to the names, flags, emblems, military flags, etc. of foreign countries, except with the consent of the government of that country;

(3) Identical or similar to the names, flags, emblems, etc. of intergovernmental international organizations, except with the consent of the organization or when they do not easily mislead the public;

(4) Identical or similar to the official marks indicating control or guarantee, or inspection marks, except with authorization;

(5) Identical or similar to the names or logos of "Red Cross" or "Red Crescent";

(6) Bearing ethnic discriminatory characteristics;

(7) Deceptive and likely to mislead the public about the characteristics or origin of the goods;

(8) Harmful to socialist ethical standards or having other adverse effects.

The names of administrative divisions at or above the county level or well-known foreign place names may not be used as trademarks. However, this does not apply if the place name has other meanings or is part of a collective trademark or certification trademark. Trademarks that have already been registered and use place names will remain valid.

The following signs may not be registered as trademarks:

(1) Only the generic name, graphic, or model of the goods;

(2) Only directly indicating the quality, main ingredients, function, purpose, weight, quantity, and other characteristics of the goods;

(3) Others lacking prominent features.

The signs listed in the preceding clause, if they have acquired distinctive features through use and are easily recognizable, may be registered as trademarks.

Famous trademarks shall be determined based on the requests of the parties involved as the facts to be identified in handling trademark-related cases. The determination of a famous trademark should take into account the following factors:

    (1) The level of awareness of the relevant public towards the trademark;

    (2) The duration of use of the trademark;

    (3) The duration, extent, and geographical scope of any promotional activities of the trademark;

    (4) The records of the trademark being protected as a famous trademark;

    (5) Other factors indicating the reputation of the trademark.

    During trademark registration examination and the investigation of trademark infringement cases by the administrative authorities for industry and commerce, if the parties assert their rights in accordance with Article 13 of this Law, the Trademark Office may make a determination on the fame of the trademark according to the needs of the examination and case handling.

    During the process of resolving trademark disputes, if the parties assert their rights in accordance with Article 13 of this Law, the Trademark Review and Adjudication Board may make a determination on the fame of the trademark according to the needs of case handling.

    During the trial of trademark civil and administrative cases, if the parties assert their rights in accordance with Article 13 of this Law, the people's court designated by the Supreme People's Court may make a determination on the fame of the trademark according to the needs of case trial.

    Producers and operators shall not use the words "Famous Trademark" on goods, product packaging or containers, or in advertising, exhibitions, and other commercial activities.

All of the following behaviors constitute an infringement of the exclusive rights of a registered trademark:

(1) Using a trademark that is identical to the registered trademark on the same type of goods without the consent of the registered trademark owner;

(2) Using a trademark that is similar to the registered trademark on the same type of goods, or using a trademark that is identical or similar to the registered trademark on similar goods, which may cause confusion, without the consent of the registered trademark owner;

(3) Selling goods that infringe the exclusive rights of a registered trademark;

(4) Counterfeiting or manufacturing someone else's registered trademark identification without authorization, or selling counterfeited or unauthorized manufactured registered trademark identification;

(5) Changing a registered trademark without the consent of the registered trademark owner and reintroducing goods with the changed trademark into the market;

(6) Intentionally providing facilitation for acts that infringe on other people's trademark exclusive rights and assisting others in committing acts that infringe on trademark exclusive rights;

(7) Causing other damages to the exclusive rights of someone's registered trademark.

If a trademark agency has one of the following behaviors, the administrative department for industry and commerce shall order it to make corrections within a specified period of time, give a warning, and impose a fine of no less than ten thousand yuan but no more than one hundred thousand yuan; give a warning and impose a fine of no less than five thousand yuan but no more than fifty thousand yuan on the directly responsible person in charge and other directly responsible personnel; if it constitutes a crime, criminal responsibility shall be pursued according to law:

(1) Forging, altering or using forged or altered legal documents, seals or signatures during the process of handling trademark matters;

(2) Using means such as defamation of other trademark agencies to solicit trademark agency business or disrupting the order of the trademark agency market by other improper means;

(3) Violating the provisions of Article 19, paragraph 3 and paragraph 4 of this Law.

If a trademark agency has the behaviors specified in the preceding paragraph, the administrative department for industry and commerce shall record it in its credit file; if the circumstances are serious, the Trademark Office and the Trademark Review and Adjudication Board may decide to stop accepting its trademark agency business and make an announcement.

If a trademark agency violates the principle of good faith and damages the legitimate interests of the client, it shall bear civil liability in accordance with the law, and shall be punished by the trademark agency industry organization in accordance with the provisions of its articles of association.

The types of principal penalties are as follows:
(1) Supervision;
(2) Detention;
(3) Fixed-term imprisonment;
(4) Life imprisonment;
(5) Death penalty.

The types of additional penalties are as follows:
(1) Fine;
(2) Deprivation of political rights;
(3) Confiscation of property.
Additional penalties can also be applied independently.

Criminal offenders subject to community correction must comply with the following regulations during the period of execution:

(1) Obey the law and administrative regulations, and submit to supervision;
(2) Without the approval of the executing authority, the right to freedom of speech, publication, assembly, association, demonstration, and protest shall not be exercised;
(3) Report one's activities according to the regulations of the executing authority;
(4) Adhere to the regulations of the executing authority regarding visitor policies;
(5) If leaving the city or county of residence or relocating, approval from the executing authority must be obtained.

Criminal offenders subject to community correction should receive equal pay for equal work during their labor.

Deprivation of political rights includes the deprivation of the following rights:
(1) The right to vote and the right to be elected;
(2) The rights to freedom of speech, press, assembly, association, demonstration, and protest;
(3) The right to hold positions in state organs;
(4) The right to hold leadership positions in state-owned companies, enterprises, institutions, and people's organizations.

For criminals sentenced to detention or imprisonment for a maximum of three years, the following conditions must be met in order to be granted probation. Probation must be declared for individuals who are under the age of eighteen, pregnant women, and those who are seventy-five years of age or older:
   (1) The crime is relatively minor;
   (2) The individual shows remorse;
   (3) There is no danger of reoffending;
   (4) Declaring probation will not have a significant negative impact on the community where the individual resides.
   When probation is declared, specific activities may be prohibited for the probationer during the probationary period based on the crime committed. They may also be restricted from entering specific areas or contacting certain individuals.
   If the probationer is also given additional penalties, those penalties must still be carried out.

Criminals who have been sentenced to probation shall abide by the following provisions:
(1) Abide by laws and administrative regulations and comply with supervision;
(2) Report their activities according to the regulations of the supervising authority;
(3) Follow the regulations of the supervising authority regarding visiting;
(4) If leaving the city or county of their residence or relocating, they shall obtain approval from the supervising authority.

Criminals who have been sentenced to community correction, detention, fixed-term imprisonment, or life imprisonment can have their sentences reduced if they comply with the prison regulations, undergo educational transformation, show genuine remorse, or demonstrate meritorious conduct. The following significant acts of meritorious conduct shall result in sentence reduction:

(1) Preventing others from committing serious crimes;
(2) Reporting and verifying serious criminal activities inside or outside the prison;
(3) Making inventions, innovations, or significant technological advancements;
(4) Sacrificing oneself to save others in daily production or life;
(5) Demonstrating outstanding performance in natural disaster relief or major accident elimination;
(6) Making other significant contributions to the nation and society.

The actual term served after sentence reduction shall not be less than the following periods:

(1) For those sentenced to community correction, detention, or fixed-term imprisonment, not less than half of the original sentence;
(2) For those sentenced to life imprisonment, not less than thirteen years;
(3) For those whose death penalty has been commuted to life imprisonment, not less than twenty-five years, and for those whose death penalty has been commuted to a twenty-five-year fixed-term imprisonment, not less than twenty years.

